X\chapter{INTRODUCTION}
X
XComputer graphics is one of the fastest growing fields
Xin the computer industry.
XComputer graphics has applications in many diverse areas, from electronic
Xgames to medicine; from cartoons to the space industry.  Just
Xwhat is interactive computer graphics and why is it so versatile?
XHuman visual perception is quite keen and communicating with a
Xcomputer is generally faster and easier
Xwith images, rather than with
Xnumbers. Furthermore, by
Xhaving the computer continuously updating a display,
Xthe display itself becomes the communications medium.
XThe user converses with the computer through the display using
Xdevices such as light pens,
Xmice, data tablets, buttons, and
Xknobs.  The response of the computer is immediately reflected
Xon the display,
Xproviding a fast communication channel between person and machine.
XThis technology is called interactive computer graphics.
X
XAs the Army's lead laboratory for vulnerability technology, the
XBallistic Research Laboratory (BRL) constantly performs
Xanalyses for a wide variety of military systems.
XThree dimensional computer models of the
Xphysical characteristics of these systems
Xare vital to these studies.
XSince the mid-1960's, BRL has used a solid modeling technique
Xcalled Combinatorial Solid Geometry (CSG or COMGEOM)
Xfor representing these models.
XThe COMGEOM technique uses
XBoolean logic operations to combine basic geometric
Xshapes or primitives to produce complex three-dimensional objects.
XThe COMGEOM geometric models are processed by
Xthe Geometric Information
XFor Targets (GIFT)
X\cite{gift1,gift2}
Xand LIBRT
X\cite{solid-models}
Xfor use in follow-on engineering analysis.
X
XGeometric models are large collections
Xof numerical data which have traditionally
Xbeen created and edited manually, and analyzed in a batch environment.
XThe production and modification of geometric models has been a slow,
Xlabor-intensive
Xprocess.
XIn 1980, BRL initiated an effort to improve the response
Xtime of the geometric modeling process by applying interactive
Xcomputer graphics techniques.
XAs a result of this work, BRL
Xdeveloped the Multi-device Graphics EDitor (MGED),
Xan interactive editor for solid models
Xbased on the COMGEOM technique.
XUsing MGED, a designer can build, view, and modify model descriptions
Xinteractively by manipulating the graphical representation,
Xreceiving immediate visual feedback on a graphics display.
XMGED replaces the manual method for the production
Xand modification of geometric models.
X
XBefore MGED was built,
Xexisting packages were evaluated with respect to
Xtheir utility for the geometric modeling process.
XQuite an exhaustive search of commercially available systems
Xwas conducted and none were found which met
Xthe BRL requirements.
XA study was initiated to examine the feasibility of producing
Xthe required capability in-house;
Xa preliminary version of MGED which
Xquite convincingly demonstrated the
Xfeasibility of such an undertaking \cite{interactive-construction}.
XIt was then decided to develop MGED into a full production code.
XProduction MGED code has been used since January 1982 to
Xbuild models interactively at BRL.
X
XThis report is intended to serve as  a user manual
Xfor the MGED program.
XThe process of viewing and editing a description using MGED
Xis covered in detail.  The internal data structure is also covered, as
Xit is an important part in the overall design.
XAll the commands will be discussed and a command summary table presented.
XAlso, a section will be devoted to the hardware interfaces for each
Xmajor class of workstations which MGED supports.
X
X\section{Philosophy}
X
XThe role of CAD models at BRL differs somewhat from
Xthat of CAD models being built in the automobile and aerospace industries,
Xresulting in some different design choices
Xbeing made in the BRL-CAD software.
XBecause BRL's main use for these models is to conduct detailed
Xperformance and survivability analyses of large complex vehicles,
Xit is required that the model of an entire vehicle be completely contained
Xin a single database suitable for interrogation by the application codes.
XThis places especially heavy demands on the database software.
XAt the same time, these analysis codes require less detail
Xthan would be required if NC machining were the primary goal.
X
XAt BRL, there are only a small number of primary designers responsible
Xfor the design of a vehicle, and for the construction of the corresponding
Xsolid model.  Together they decide upon and construct the
Xoverall structure of the model,
Xthen they perform the work of building substructures in parallel,
Xconstantly combining intermediate results into the full model database.
XBecause of the need to produce rapid prototypes (often creating a full design
Xwithin a few weeks), there is no time for a separate integration stage;
Xsubsystem integration must be an ongoing part of the design process.
X
XOnce an initial vehicle design is completed, there is usually the
Xneed for exploring many alternatives.  Typically, between three and twelve
Xvariations of each design need to be produced, analyzed, and optimized
Xbefore recommendations for the final design can be made.
XAlso, there is a constantly changing definition of performance;
Xnew developments may necessitate rapidly re-evaluating
Xall the designs of the past several years for trouble spots.
X
XThe user interface is designed to be powerful and ``expert friendly'' rather
Xthan foolproof for a novice to use.
XHowever, it only takes about two days for new users to start doing useful
Xdesign work with MGED.
XTrue proficiency comes with a few months practice.
X
XFinally, it is vitally important that the software offer the same capabilities
Xand user interface across a wide variety of display and processor hardware.
XGovernment procurement regulations make single-vendor solutions difficult.
XThe best way to combat this is with highly portable software.
X
X\section{Displays Supported}
X
XIt is important for a CAD system to have a certain degree of independence
Xfrom any single display device in order to provide longevity of the
Xsoftware and freedom from a single equipment supplier.
XThe MGED editor supports serial use of multiple displays by way of
Xan object-oriented programmatic
Xinterface between the editor proper and the display-specific code.
XAll display-specific code for each type of hardware is isolated
Xin a separate {\em display manager} module.
XHigh performance of the display manager was an important design goal.
XExisting graphics libraries
Xwere considered, but no well established standard existed with the necessary
Xperformance and 3-dimensional constructs.
XBy having the display manager modules incorporated as a direct part of
Xthe MGED editor, the high rates of display update necessary to deliver
Xtrue interactive response are possible, even when using CPUs of modest power.
X
XAn arbitrary number of
Xdisplay managers may be included in a copy of MGED, allowing the user
Xto rapidly and conveniently move his editing session from display to display.
XThis is useful for switching between several displays, each of
Xwhich may have unique benefits:  one might have color capability,
Xand another might have depth cueing.
XThe {\bf release} command closes out MGED's use of the current
Xdisplay, and does an implicit attach to the ``null'' display manager.
XThis can be useful to allow another user to briefly examine an image
Xon the same display hardware without having to lose the state of
Xthe MGED editing session.  The {\bf attach} command is used to
Xattach to a new display via it's appropriate display manager routines.
XIf another display is already attached, it is released first.
XThe null display manager also allows the MGED editor to be run from a normal
Xalphanumeric terminal with no graphic display at all.  This can be useful
Xwhen the only tasks at hand involve viewing or changing
Xdatabase structures, or entering or adjusting geometry parameters
Xin numerical form.
X
XCreation of a new display manager module in the ``{\bf C}'' language
X\cite{c-prog-lang}
Xgenerally takes an experienced
Xprogrammer from one to three days.
XThe uniform interface to the display manager provides two levels
Xof interactive support.
XThe first level of display support includes
Xthe Tektronix 4014, 4016, and compatible displays,
Xincluding the Teletype 5620 bit-mapped displays.
XHowever, while storage-tube style display devices allow MGED to
Xdeliver the correct functionality, they lack the
Xrate of screen refresh needed for productive interaction.
XThe second level of support, including real-time interaction,
Xis provided by
Xthe Vector General 3300 displays,
Xthe Megatek 7250 and 7255 displays,
Xthe Raster Technologies Model One/180 display,
Xthe Evans and Sutherland PS300 displays
Xwith either serial, parallel, or Ethernet attachment,
Xthe Sun workstations,
Xand the Silicon Graphics IRIS workstation family.
X
X\section{Portability}
X
XToday, the half-life of computer technology is
Xapproximately two to three years.
XTo realize proper longevity of the modeling software, it needs to be written
Xin a portable language to allow the software to be moved readily from
Xprocessor to processor without requiring the modeling software or users
Xto change.
XThen, when it is desirable to
Xtake advantage of the constantly increasing
Xprocessor capabilities and similarly increasing memory capacity by replacing
Xthe installed hardware base, there are a minimum of ancillary costs.
XAlso, it may be desirable to connect together processors from a variety
Xof vendors, with the workload judiciously allocated to
Xthe types of hardware that best support the requirements of each particular
Xapplication program.
XThis distribution of processing when coupled with the fact that
Xusers are spread out over multiple locations makes networking a vital
Xingredient as well.
X
XBRL's strategy for achieving this high level of portability was to target
Xall the software for the UNIX operating system,
X\cite{unix-ts-sys},
Xwith all the software written in the ``{\bf C}''
Xprogramming language \cite{c-prog-lang}.
XThe entire BRL-CAD Package, including the MGED editor
Xis currently running on all UNIX machines at BRL,
Xunder several versions of the UNIX operating system, including
XBerkeley 4.3 BSD UNIX, Berkeley 4.2 BSD UNIX, and AT\&T System V UNIX.
X
XThe list of manufacturers and models of CPUs that support the UNIX
Xoperating system \cite{modern-tools-hi-res}
Xis much too lengthy to include here.  However, BRL
Xhas experience using this software on
XDEC VAX 11/750, 11/780, 11/785 processors,
XGould PN6000 and PN9000 processors,
XAlliant FX/8 and FX/80 processors (including systems with eight CPUs),
XSilicon Graphics IRIS 2400, 2400 Turbo, 3030, 4-D, and 4-D/GT workstations,
Xthe Cray X-MP, the Cray-2,
Xand the ill-fated Denelcor HEP H-1000 parallel supercomputer.
X
X\section{Object-Oriented Design}
X
XThe central editor code has four sets of object-oriented interfaces
Xto various subsystems, including database access, geometry processing,
Xdisplay management, and command parser/human interface.
XIn each case, a common interface has been defined for the set of
Xfunctions that implement the subsystem;
Xmultiple instances of these function sets can exist.
XThe routines in each instance of a subsystem are completely independent
Xof all the routines in other functions sets, making it easy to add new
Xinstances of the subsystem.  A new type of primitive geometry,
Xa new display manager, a new database interface, or a new command
Xprocessor can each be added simply by writing all the routines
Xto implement a new subsystem.
XThis approach greatly simplifies software maintenance, and allows
Xdifferent groups to have responsibility for the
Xcreation and enhancement of features within each of the subsystems.
X
X\chapter{THE COMBINATORIAL GEOMETRY METHODOLOGY}
X
X\section{Background}
X
XSince the MGED system is presently based on the COMGEOM solid modeling
Xtechnique, a brief overview of the COMGEOM technique is required
Xto effectively use MGED.
XFor more detailed information on the COMGEOM technique see
X\cite{gift1,gift2}.
X
X\begin{figure}[tb]
X\begin{tabular}{l l}
XSymbol & Name \\
X\\
XARS	& Arbitrary Triangular Surfaced Polyhedron \\
XARB	& Arbitrary Convex Polyhedron \\
XELLG	& General Ellipsoid \\
XPOLY	& Polygonal Faceted Solid \\
XSPL	& Non-Uniform Rational B-Spline (NURB) \\
XTGC	& Truncated General Cone \\
XTOR	& Torus \\
XHALF	& Half Space (Plane)
X\end{tabular}
X\caption{Basic Solid Types \label{list-of-basic-solids} }
X\end{figure}
X\begin{figure}[tb]
X\begin{tabular}{l l}
XSymbol & Name \\
X\\
XRPP	& Rectangular Parallelpiped \\
XBOX	& Box \\
XRAW	& Right Angle Wedge \\
XSPH	& Sphere \\
XRCC	& Right Circular Cylinder \\
XREC	& Right Elliptical Cylinder \\
XTRC	& Truncated Right Cylinder \\
XTEC	& Truncated Elliptical Cylinder \\
X\end{tabular}
X\caption{Special-Case Solid Types \label{list-of-special-case-solids} }
X\end{figure}
XThe COMGEOM technique utilizes two basic entities - a solid and a region.
XA solid is defined as one of fifteen basic geometric shapes or
Xprimitives.  Figure \ref{list-of-basic-solids} lists the
Xbasic solid types, and Figure \ref{list-of-special-case-solids}
Xlists special cases of the basic solid types for which support exists.
XThe individual parameters of each solid define the solid's
Xlocation, size, and orientation.  A region is a combination of
Xone or more solids and is defined as the volume occupied
Xby the resulting combination of solids.
XSolids are combined into regions using any of three logic
Xoperations: union (OR), intersection (+), or difference (-).
XThe union of two solids is defined as the volume in either
Xof the solids.
XThe difference of two solids is defined as the volume of the first
Xsolid minus the volume of the second solid.
XThe intersection of two solids is defined as the volume
Xcommon to both solids.
X%%% XXX Figure 1 presents a graphical representation of these operations.
X
XAny number of solids may be combined to produce a region.
XAs far as the COMGEOM technique is concerned, only a region can
Xrepresent an actual component of the model.
XRegions are homogeneous;  they are composed of a single material.
XEach region represents a single object in the model;
Xthe solids are only building blocks which are combined to
Xdefine the {\em shape} of the regions.
XSince regions represent the components of the model, they
Xare further identified by code numbers.
XThese code numbers either identify the region as
Xa model component (nonzero item code)
Xor as air (nonzero air code).
XAny volume not defined as a region is assumed to be ``universal air'' and
Xis given an air code of ``01''.
XIf it is necessary to distinguish between universal ``01'' air and any
Xother kind of air, then that volume must be defined as a region
Xand given an air code other than ``01''.
XNormally, regions cannot occupy the same volume (overlap),
Xbut regions identified with
Xair codes can overlap with any region identified as a component
X(i.e. one that has a nonzero item code).
XRegions identified with different air codes, however, can not overlap.
X
X\section{Directed Acyclic Graph and Database Details}
X
XOne of the critical aspects of a graphics software package
Xis its internal data structure.
XSince geometric models often result
Xin very large volumes of data being generated,
Xthe importance of the data structure here is emphasized.
XThus it is felt that a brief introduction to the
Xorganization of the MGED database is
Ximportant for all users.
X
XThe database is stored as a single,
Xbinary, direct-access
XUNIX file for efficiency and cohesion,
Xwith fixed length records called database {\em granules}.
XEach object occupies one or more granules of storage.
XThe user sees and manipulates the directed acyclic graphs
Xlike UNIX paths (e.g., car/chassis/door),
Xbut in a global namespace.
XThere can be many independent or semi-independent
Xdirected acyclic graphs within the same database,
Xeach defining different models.
XThe figure also makes heavy use of the {\em instancing} capability.
XAs mentioned earlier, the
X{\em leaves} of the graph are the primitive solids.
X
XCommands exist to import sub-trees from other databases and libraries,
Xand to export sub-trees to other databases.
XAlso, converters exist to dump databases in printable form for
Xnon-binary interchange.
X
X\section{Model Building Philosophy}
X
XThe power of a full directed acyclic graph structure for representing
Xthe organization of the database gives a designer a great deal of
Xflexibility in structuring a model.
XIn order to prevent chaos, most designers at BRL choose to
Xdesign the overall structure of their model in a top-down manner,
Xselecting meaningful names for the major structures and sub-structures
Xwithin the model.
XActual construction of the details of the
Xmodel generally proceeds in a bottom-up
Xmanner, where each sub-system is fabricated from component primitives.
X
XThe first sub-systems to be constructed are the chassis and skin of the
Xvehicle, after which a set of analyses are run to validate the geometry,
Xchecking for unintentional gaps in the skin or for solids which overlap.
XThe second stage of model construction is to build the features of the
Xmain compartments of the vehicle.  If necessary for the analysis
Xcodes that will be used, the different types of air compartments within
Xthe model also need to be described.
XThe final stage of model construction is to build the internal
Xobjects to the desired level of detail.
XThis might include modeling engines, transmissions, radios,
Xpeople, seats, etc.
XIn this stage of modeling, the experienced designer will draw heavily on the
Xparts-bin of model components and on pieces extracted from earlier
Xmodels, modifying those existing structures to meet his particular
Xrequirements.
X
XThroughout the model building process it is important for the model builder
Xto choose part names carefully, as the MGED database currently has a
Xglobal name space, with individual node names limited to 16 characters.
XIn addition, BRL has defined conventions for naming the elements in the
Xtop three levels of database structure,
Xallowing people to
Xeasily navigate within models prepared at
Xdifferent times by different designers.
XThis naming convention
Xfacilitates the integration of design changes into existing models.
X
X\chapter{THE BASIC EDITING PROCESS}
X
X\section{Interaction Forms}
X
XTextual and numeric interaction with the MGED editor is the most
Xprecise editing paradigm because it allows exact
Xmanipulation of known configurations.
XThis works well when the user is designing the model
Xfrom an existing drawing, or when all dimensions are known (or are computable)
Xin advance.
X
XThe use of a
Xtablet or mouse, knob-box or dial-box, buttons, and a joystick
Xare all simultaneously supported by MGED for analog inputs.
XDirect graphic interaction via a ``point-push-pull'' editing paradigm
Xtends to be better for
Xprototyping, developing arbitrary geometry, and fitting
Xtogether poorly specified configurations.
XHaving both types of interaction capability available at all times
Xallows the user to select the style of interaction that best
Xmeets his immediate requirements.
X
X\section{The Faceplate}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{faceplate.ps}
X\caption{The MGED Editor Faceplate.}
X\label{faceplate}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{buttonmenu.ps}
X\caption{The Pop-Up Button Menu.}
X\label{buttonmenu}
X\end{figure}
X
XWhen the MGED program has a display device attached, it
Xdisplays a border around the region of the screen being used
Xalong with some ancillary status information.  Together, this
Xinformation is termed the editor ``faceplate''.
XSee Figure \ref{faceplate}.
XIn the upper left corner of the display is a small enclosed area
Xwhich is used to display the current editor state;
Xthis is discussed further in the Editor States section, below.
X
XUnderneath the state display is a zone in which three ``pop-up'' menus
Xmay appear.
XThe top menu is termed the ``button menu,'' as it
Xcontains menu items which duplicate many of the functions assigned to
Xthe button box.
XHaving these frequently used
Xfunctions available on a pop-up menu
Xcan greatly decrease the number of times that the user needs to remove
Xhis hand from the pointing device (either mouse or tablet puck)
Xto reach for the buttons.
XAn example of the faceplate and first level menu is shown in
XFigure \ref{buttonmenu}.
XThe second menu is used primarily for the various editing states,
Xat which time it contains all the editing operations which are generic
Xacross all objects (scaling, rotation, and translation).
XThe third menu contains selections for object-specific editing operations.
XThe choices on these menus are detailed below.
X
XIt is important to note that while some display hardware that MGED runs on
Xhas inherent support for pop-up menus included, MGED does not
Xpresently take advantage of that support, preferring to depend
Xon the portable menu system within MGED instead.
XIt is not clear whether the slight increase in functionality that might
Xaccrue from using display-specific menu capabilities would offset the
Xslight nuisance of a non-uniform user interface.
X
XRunning across the entire bottom of the faceplate is a thin rectangular
Xdisplay area which holds two lines of text.
XThe first line always contains a numeric display of the model-space
Xcoordinates of the center of the view and the current size of
Xthe viewing cube, both in the currently selected editing units.
XThe first line also contains the current rotation rates.
XThe second line has several uses, depending on editor mode.
XNormally it displays the formal name of the database that is being
Xedited, but in various editing states this second line will instead
Xcontain certain path selection information.
XWhen the angle/distance cursor function is activated, the second
Xline will be used to display the current settings of the cursor.
X
XIt is important to mention that while the database records all
Xdata in terms of the fixed base unit of millimeters, all numeric interaction between
Xthe user and the editor are in terms of user-selected display [or local] units.
XThe user may select from millimeters, centimeters, meters, inches, and
Xfeet, and the currently active display units are noted in the first
Xdisplay line.
X
XThe concept of the ``viewing cube'' is an important one.
XObjects drawn on the screen are clipped in X, Y, and Z, to the size
Xindicated on the first status line.
XThis feature allows extraneous wireframes which are positioned within view
Xin X and Y, but quite far away in the Z direction to not be seen,
Xkeeping the display free from irrelevant objects when zooming in.
XSome display managers can selectively enable and disable Z axis clipping
Xas a viewing aid.
X
X\section{The Screen Coordinate System}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{coord-axes.ps}
X\caption{The Screen Coordinate System.}
X\label{coord-axes}
X\end{figure}
X
XThe MGED editor uses the standard right-handed
Xscreen coordinate system,
Xas shown in Figure \ref{coord-axes}.
XThe Z axis is perpendicular to the screen and the positive Z direction is
Xout of the screen.  The directions of positive (+) and negative (-) axis
Xrotations are also indicated.  For these rotations, the ``Right
XHand Rule'' applies:  Point the thumb of the right hand along the direction
Xof +X axis and the other fingers will describe the sense of positive
Xrotation.
X
X\section{Changing the View}
X
XAt any time in an editing session, the user may add one or more
Xsubtrees to the active model space.  If the viewing cube is
Xsuitably positioned, the newly added subtrees are drawn on the display.
X(The ``reset'' function can always be activated to get the entire active
Xmodel space into view).
XThe normal mode of operation is for users to work with wireframe
Xdisplays of the unevaluated primitive solids.  These wireframes can be
Xcreated from the database very rapidly.
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{crod.ps}
X\caption{An Engine Connecting Rod.}
X\label{crod}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{crod-close.ps}
X\caption{Close-Up Connecting Rod, Showing Z-clipping.}
X\label{crod-close}
X\end{figure}
X
XOn demand, the user can request the calculation of
Xapproximate boundary wireframes that account for
Xall of the boolean operations specified along the arcs of the
Xdirected acyclic graph in the database.
XThis is a somewhat time consuming process, so it is not used
Xby default, but it is quite reasonable to use whenever the
Xdesign has reached a plateau.
XNote that these boundary wireframes are not stored in the database,
Xand are generally used as a visualization aid for the designer.
XFigure \ref{crod} shows an engine connecting rod.
XOn the left side is the wireframe of the unevaluated primitives
Xthat the part is modeled with, and on the right side is the approximate
Xboundary wireframe that results from evaluating the boolean expressions.
X
XAlso, at any time the user can cause any part of the active model space
Xto be dropped from view.
XThis is most useful when joining two complicated subsystems
Xtogether;  the first would be called up into the active model space,
Xmanipulated until ready, and then the second subsystem would also be
Xcalled up as well.  When any necessary adjustments had been made,
Xperhaps to eliminate overlaps or to change positioning tolerances,
Xone of the subassemblies could be dropped from view,
Xand editing could proceed.
X
XThe position, size, and orientation of the viewing cube can be
Xarbitrarily changed during an editing session.
XThe simplest way to change the view is by selecting one of nine
Xbuilt in preset views, which can be accomplished by a simple keyboard
Xcommand, or by way of a button press or first level menu selection.
XThe view can be rotated and translated to any arbitrary position.
XThe user is given the ability to execute a {\bf save view} button/menu
Xfunction that attaches the current view to a {\bf restore view} button/menu
Xfunction.
X
XThe rate of rotation around each of the X, Y, and Z axes
Xcan be selected by knob, joystick, or keyboard command.
XBecause the rotation is specified as a rate, the view
Xwill continue to rotate about the view center until the rotation
Xrate is returned to zero.
X(A future version of MGED will permit selection of rate or value
Xoperation of the knobs).
XSimilarly, the zoom rate (in or out) can be set by keyboard
Xcommand or by rotating a control dial.
XAlso, displays with three or more mouse buttons have binary (2x) zoom
Xfunctions assigned to two of the buttons.
XFinally, it is possible to set a slew rate to translate the view
Xcenter along any axis in the current viewing space, selectable
Xeither by keyboard command or control dial.
XIn VIEW state, the main mouse button translates the
Xview center;  the button is defined to cause the indicated point to become
Xthe center of the view.
X
XThe assignment of zoom and slew functions to the mouse buttons tends to
Xmake wandering around in a large model very straightforward.
XThe user uses the binary zoom-out button to get an overall view, then
Xmoves the new area for inspection to the center of the view and uses
Xthe binary zoom-in button to obtain a ``close up'' view.
XFigure \ref{crod-close}
Xshows such a close up view of the engine connecting rod.
XNotice how the wireframe is clipped in the Z viewing direction
Xto fit within the viewing cube.
X
X\section{Model Navigation}
X
XIn order to assist the user in creating and manipulating a complicated
Xhierarchical model structure, there is a whole family of editor commands
Xfor examining and searching the database.
XIn addition, on all keyboard commands, UNIX-style regular-expression
Xpattern matching, such as ``*axle*'' or ``wheel[abcd]'', can be used.
XThe simplest editor command ({\bf t}) prints a table of contents, or directory,
Xof the node names used in the model.  If no parameters are specified,
Xall names in the model are printed,
Xotherwise only those specified are printed.
XThe names of solids are printed unadorned, while the names of combination
X(non-terminal) nodes are printed with a slash (``/'') appended to them.
X
XIf the user is interested in obtaining detailed information about the
Xcontents of a node, the list ({\bf l}) command will provide it.
XFor combination (non-terminal) nodes, the information about all departing
Xarcs is printed, including the names of the nodes referenced, the boolean
Xexpressions being used, and an indication of any translations and rotations
Xbeing applied.
XFor leaf nodes, the primitive solid-specific ``describe yourself''
Xfunction is invoked, which provides a formatted display of the parameters
Xof that solid.
X
XThe {\bf tops} command is used to find the names of all nodes which are
Xnot referenced by any non-terminal nodes;  such nodes are either
Xunattached leaf nodes, or tree tops.
XTo help visualize the tree structure of the database,
Xthe {\bf tree} command exists to
Xprint an approximate representation of the database subtree below the
Xnamed nodes.
XThe {\bf find} command can be used to find the names of all non-terminal
Xnodes which reference the indicated node name(s).  This can be very helpful
Xwhen trying to decide how to modify an existing model.
XA related command ({\bf paths}) finds the full tree path specifications
Xwhich contain a specified graph fragment, such as ``car/axle/wheel''.
XIn addition to these commands, several more commands exist
Xto support specialized types of searching through the model database.
X
X\section{Editor States}
X
XThe MGED editor operates in one of six states.
XEither of the two PICK states can be entered by button press,
Xmenu selection, or keyboard command.  The selection of the desired
Xobject can be made either by using {\em illuminate mode}, or by
Xkeyboard entry of the name of the object.
X
XIlluminate mode is arranged such that if there are {\bf n} objects visible on
Xthe screen, then the screen is divided into {\bf n} horizontal bands.
XBy moving the cursor (via mouse or tablet) up and down through these bands,
Xthe user will cause each solid in turn to be highlighted on the screen,
Xwith the solid's name displayed in the faceplate.
XThe center mouse button is pressed when the desired solid is located, causing
Xa transition to the next state (Object Path, or Solid Edit).
X
XIlluminate mode offers significant advantages over more conventional pointing
Xmethods when the desired object lies in a densely populated region of the
Xscreen.  In such cases, pointing methods have a high chance of making an
Xincorrect selection.
XHowever, in sparsely populated regions of the screen, a pointing paradigm
Xwould be more convenient, and future versions of MGED will support this.
X
X\section{Model Units}
X
XAll databases start with an ``ident'' record which contains
Xa title string that identifies the model, the
Xcurrent local units (eg, mm, cm or inches) of the model,
Xand a database version identification number.
XAs noted, all numerical information
Xin the database is stored in the fixed base
Xunit of millimeters,
Xand all work (input and output) is done in a user-selected local unit.
XThe user can change his local unit at any time
Xby using the {\bf units} command.
XThis way of handling units was selected to free the user from worrying
Xabout units conversion when components are drawn from the ``parts bin''.
