X\chapter{PERIPHERAL DEVICES}
X
XBefore we discuss the features of MGED, we will introduce
Xthe hardware devices used to implement them.
XThese devices are the ``tools of the trade'' for the MGED user.
XWe will discuss only basic operational characteristics here.
XSpecific use of these devices will be covered in the later sections
Xon the viewing and editing features of MGED.
X
X\section{Joystick}
X
XThe joystick is a mechanical device used to do rotations in MGED.
XAny movement left or right rotates the display about the
XX-axis.  Any movement up or down rotates the display
Xabout the Y-axis.  When the joystick top is twisted in a clockwise or
Xcounterclockwise direction, the display rotates about the Z-axis.
XAny combination motion of the joystick will produce a ``combined''
Xrotation about the appropriate axes.
XAs implemented on the Vector General hardware,
Xall of these motions have a spring return to a null center position.
X
X\section{Button Box}
X
XThe button box contains a collection of buttons.
XOn each button is a light that can be lit under program control.
XPressing a button sends a ``press'' event to MGED,
Xand results in an action occurring, or a condition being set.
XThe exact functions assigned to these buttons will be discussed
Xin the sections on viewing the display and on editing.
X
X\subsection{Vector General Buttons}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{fig-vg-buttons.ps}
X\caption{Vector General Button Assignments}
X\label{vg-buttons}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{fig-sgi-buttons.ps}
X\caption{Silicon Graphics Button Assignments}
X\label{sgi-buttons}
X\end{figure}
X
X% \gluein 4.5in by 4.5in, Vector General Button Assignments, vg-buttons.
X% XXX \gluein 4.5in by 4in, Megatek Dial and Button Box, mg-buttons.
XThe Vector General has thirty-two buttons.
XFigure \ref{vg-buttons} depicts the functions programmed
Xfor each button.
XThe buttons in the shaded area are used for editing while the
Xrest are used for viewing the display.
X
X\subsection{Megatek Buttons}
X
X\begin{figure}[tbp]
X\begin{tabular}{rl}
XButton  & Function\\
X \\
X1       & View Mode:  Restores View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Translation in the Object-Edit mode \\
X2       & View Mode:  Saves View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Translation in the Object-Edit mode \\
X3 \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Saves the model being displayed on the screen \\
