X8 \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Rejects display and returns to Viewing display \\
X9       & View Mode:  Bottom View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Scaling in the Solid-Edit mode \\
X10      & View Mode:  Left View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Rotation in the Solid-Edit mode \\
X11      & View Mode:  Rear View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Translation in the Solid-Edit mode \\
X12      & View Mode:  90, 90 View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Restores Edit mode menu \\
X13      & View Mode:  Top View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Transfers from Viewing to Solid Pick \\
X14      & View Mode:  Right View \\
X        & Edit Mode:  Transfers from Viewing to Object Pick \\
X15      & View Mode:  Front View \\
X \\
X16      & View Mode:  35/45 View
X\end{tabular}
X\caption{Megatek Buttons \label{mg-button-table} }
X\end{figure}
X
XThe Megatek button box
Xis a general purpose input/output device that communicates with
XMGED through an intelligent control unit.  The device has eight
Xrotatable knobs and 16 buttons with lights.
X% XXX See Figure \ref{mg-buttons}.
XThe ``buttons'' and ``knobs'' of the Megateks are located in the same box.
XThere are not enough buttons to have just one assigned meaning, hence
Xmost buttons have dual functions.
XTo toggle the functions of the buttons,
Xuse the upper right button (toggle button).
XWhen the light on this button is ON, the functions listed on the RIGHT above
Xeach button is the current function.
XWhen the light on the ``toggle'' button is OFF, the functions labeled on the
XLEFT are then in effect.
XThe left/right meaning of these buttons is grouped generally according to
Xviewing functions on the left and editing functions on the right.
X
XFigure \ref{mg-button-table}
Xsummarizes the uses of the buttons.
XDepressing the button switches the light on and off.  Many of these serve a
Xdual role depending upon the selected mode - viewing or editing.  The mode is
Xselected by depressing button 4.  If light 4 is off, the system is performing
Xin the viewing mode, and the commands shown in the top half of the table are
Xexecuted.  If light 4 is on, the system is performing in the edit mode, and
Xthe commands shown in the bottom half are executed.
X
X\subsection{Silicon Graphics Buttons}
X
XThe button box layout for the SGI Iris is given
Xin Figure \ref{sgi-buttons}.
XNote that the ``right'' button shows you the right side of the
Xmodel, as if you were looking in from the left.
XTo achieve the customary draftsman views, this function
Xgoes on the left.
X
XThe upper left button is the {\bf help} key.
XIf this button is held down, and any other button (or knob)
Xis activated, a descriptive string is displayed in the eight character
XLED display on the button box.
XThe upper right button is used to reset all the knobs to zero.
XThis is useful to halt a runaway rotation or zoom operation.
X
