X%\end{figure}
X
X\section{Knobs (Dials)}
X
XThe knobs (or control dials) are used to send digital information
Xto the computer.
XAs a knob is turned, a succession of numbers are available for
Xuse by the computer.
XThe knobs can be used to rotate a displayed object about the x, y, or z
Xaxis, translate the object along the x or y axis, and change the size of the
Xview.  Action performed by these knobs is continuous and is initiated by
Xturning the knob in the proper direction and terminated by turning the knob
Xin the opposite direction.
X
X\subsection{Vector General Knobs}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{fig-vg-knobs.ps}
X\caption{Vector General Knob Assignments}
X\label{vg-knobs}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{fig-sgi-knobs.ps}
X\caption{Silicon Graphics Knob Assignments}
X\label{sgi-knobs}
X\end{figure}
X
X% \gluein 4.5in by 3.5in, Vector General Knobs, vg-knobs.
X% \gluein 4.5in by 3.5in, Silicon Graphics Knobs, sgi-knobs.
XFigure \ref{vg-knobs} depicts the functions assigned to each of the ten knobs.
XThe exact functions of each of these knobs will be discussed in
Xthe angle distance cursor section and in the viewing features section.
X
X\subsection{Megatek Knobs}
X
XThe ``buttons'' and ``knobs'' of the Megateks are located in the same box.
X% XXX as shown in Figure \ref{mg-buttons}.
XThere are not enough knobs to have ONE assigned meaning, hence
Xthree knobs have dual functions.
XThe second function of the first three knobs is only in effect when
Xthe angle-distance cursor (ADC) is on the screen.
X
X\subsection{Silicon Graphics Knobs}
X
XFigure \ref{sgi-knobs} depicts the functions assigned to the
Xeight knobs on the Silicon Graphics knob box.
XIn normal operation, the left knobs provide rotations,
Xand the right knobs provide translations and zooming.
XWhen the angle/distance cursor is activated, some of the
Xknobs are redefined.
X
X\section{Mouse or Data Tablet}
X
XMoving the mouse or the data tablet ``pen'' causes a cursor
Xon the screen to move.
XThe screen X-Y coordinates of the cursor can be sensed by MGED
Xat any time.
XClicking one of the mouse buttons,
Xor depressing the tip of the pen, results in MGED receiving
Xa special event notification.
XThe meaning of this mouse event depends on the current editing mode
Xand which portion of the display faceplate that the cursor is located
Xin.
X
XBelow is a list of some of the functions the mouse is used for in MGED;
X\begin{itemize}
X\item
XSelecting editing menus, edit functions (move faces, move edges
Xetc.) and viewing functions (selected from main edit menu); move
Xpointer to appropriate edit function and press center mouse button.
X\item
XPointing functions; interactively positioning solid primitive
Xrelative to other solids with positioning or size update being
Xdisplayed at the same time, position pointer where required and click
Xcenter mouse button.
X\item
XScaling of view size; enlarge or reduce for a more detailed view of
Xobject, left button shrinks view size, right button enlarges view
Xsize.
X\item
XDuring the solid or object illuminate phase of editing,
Xthe screen is divided into
Xinvisible horizontal sections.
XThe available selections are scanned by moving the mouse up and down.
X\item
XWhen MGED is is the viewing state,
Xand a mouse event is received which is not in the menu area of the faceplate,
Xthe point at which the cursor is pointing at will be translated to become
Xthe center of the current view.
XBy pointing and clicking the center mouse button,
Xthe center of the viewing cube
Xcan be moved to allow close-up viewing of different areas in your
Xmodel.
X\end{itemize}
X
X\subsection{Vector General Data Tablet}
X
XPosition information is entered using a pen-like stylus.
XThe distance this pen is from the tablet is important.
XIf the pen tip is within one half inch of the tablet surface, the cursor
Xlocation on the screen corresponds to the X,Y location of the
Xpen on the tablet.  This condition is called the ``near'' position.
XIf the pen is more than one half inch from the tablet surface, the
Xcursor remains located in the center of the screen.
XWhen the pen is pressed against the tablet surface,
Xthe pressure switch is activated and a ``mouse'' event
Xis sent to MGED.
X
X\subsection{Megatek Data Tablet}
X
XSome Megatek systems enter position data on the data tablet
Xusing a pen-like stylus.
XIf the tip of the stylus is
Xwithin one-half inch of the surface of the tablet, a ``star'' corresponding
Xto this location is displayed on the display screen.  If the tip is moved
Xmore than one-half inch from the surface, the position of the star remains
Xfixed.  When the stylus is pressed against the tablet surface, the pressure
Xswitch is activated and a ``mouse'' event is sent MGED.
X
XOther Megatek data tablets have a mouse instead of a pen.
XThis mouse has four buttons on it.
XThe yellow (top) button is used during illumination and editing just as the
Xpen on the Vector General terminals.
XHowever, in the viewing mode, when pushed, the point which it was pointing
Xat will be drawn at the center of the screen.
XThe blue (bottom) button has this same function at ALL times and is used
Xto ``slew'' the display during editing.
XThe white (left) and the green (right) buttons on the mouse are used for
Xzooming the display at a fixed rate.
XThe white button will zoom out and the green button will zoom in.
X
X\subsection{Silicon Graphics Mouse}
X
XThe left and right mouse buttons are used for binary (2x) zooming,
Xand the center mouse button is used for all other MGED mouse functions.
X
XOn the Silicon Graphics 3-D workstations, MGED can be run directly,
Xor it can be run under the window manager MEX.  In both cases,
XMGED opens two windows, one outlined in white for all text interaction,
Xand one outlined in yellow for all graphics display.
XWhen running MGED directly (without MEX), all mouse events are
Xsent the MGED, regardless of where the mouse is pointing.
XIn order to shift emphasis between the graphics and text windows,
Xthe smaller one can be enlarged by pointing the cursor within the
Xboundaries of the smaller window, and pressing the center button.
XThis enlarges that window, and reduces the size of the other window.
X
XWhen MEX is running, it is necessary to follow the MEX convention of
Xmoving the cursor into the desired window, and clicking the right mouse
Xbutton, to ``attach'' all input to that window.
XThis has the unfortunate consequence of requiring a lot of extra
Xmouse clicking, because the graphics window needs to be attached
Xwhen using the buttons, knobs, and mouse, while the text window
Xneeds to be attached in order to enter keyboard commands.
X
XOn the Silicon Graphics 4-D workstations running 4Sight,
Xmouse events are sent to MGED only when the cursor is within the
Xboundaries of the MGED graphics window.
X
X\subsection{Sun Workstation Mouse}
X
XOn the Sun workstation, MGED must be run in a {\bf suntools} window.
XThe main consequence of this is that mouse events are sent to MGED
Xonly when the cursor is within the boundaries of the MGED graphics window
Xon the screen.
XThe left and right mouse buttons are used for binary (2x) zooming,
Xand the center mouse button is used for all other MGED mouse functions.
X
X\section{Keyboard}
X
XThe keyboard is used to issue commands and supply parameters to MGED.
XIt is also used to login and logout of the UNIX system, and to
Xrun other UNIX programs.
XAll characters typed on the keyboard,
Xwith the exception of the user's password, are displayed (echoed) on the
Xmonitor.
XIn this text, all input typed by the user is
Xshown in {\em italics}, while all literal MGED output
Xis shown in {\tt typewriter font}.
XAll entries are
Xterminated by depressing the RETURN key.
XThis action immediately precedes the execution of the directive.
XIn most cases, lower case letters
Xmust be used.  A space must be used between the command and its
Xarguments.
XEmbedded blanks are not allowed.
XEntering Control/H causes cursor to backspace and erase entered
Xinformation.
XAn MGED command is interrupted by entering Control/C.
XEnd-of-File is sent to MGED by entering Control/D.
XThe graphics editor displays the prompt
X\begin{verbatim}
X	mged>
X\end{verbatim}
Xon the display whenever it is ready to accept a command from the keyboard.
X
X\chapter{OPERATING INSTRUCTIONS}
X
X\section{Entering the Graphics Editor}
X
XType {\em mged filename}, e.g.:
X\begin{verbatim}
X     mged s_axle.g
X     mged shaft.g
X     mged fred.g
X\end{verbatim}
Xwhere the filename is the name of the UNIX file in which
Xyour object description data is stored.
XIt is conventional that the
Xextension ``.g'' on the filename
Xsignifies a graphics file, and is a good practice, but is not required.
XIf the named database does not already exist,
XMGED will ask if it should create a new database.
XMGED will ask:
X
X{\tt \begin{verse}
X\% {\em mged new.g} \\
XBRL-CAD Release 3.0 Graphics Editor (MGED) \\
X\ \ \ \ Tue Sep 6 02:52:55 EDT 1988 \\
X\ \ \ \ mike@video:/cad/mged.4d \\
Xnew.g: No such file or directory \\
XCreate new database (y|n)[n]? {\em y} \\
Xattach (nu|tek|tek4109|ps|plot|sgi)[nu]? {\em sgi} \\
XATTACHING sgi (SGI 4d) \\
XUntitled MGED Database (units=mm) \\
Xmged>
X\end{verse} }
XHere, the {\em italic} type indicates the user's response:
X{\em y} instructs MGED to create the new database, and
X{\em sgi} instructs MGED to attach to a window
Xon the Silicon Graphics (SGI) workstation.
X
XDirectives to the graphics editor are made by
X\begin{enumerate}
X\item entering information from the keyboard,
Xshown here in the text by the use of {\em italics},
X\item using the stylus to select items from
Xthe menu (select), and
X\item pressing buttons and twisting knobs on the
Xfunction control box (press, twist).
X\end{enumerate}
X
XThe prompt for a command is {\tt mged>}.
X
X\subsection{Running MGED on a Silicon Graphics}
X
XWhen running MGED from the console of a Silicon Graphics workstation,
XMGED retains the text window from which it was started,
Xand opens a second window for the graphics display.
XBy default, the graphics window is quite large, and the text window
Xis rather small.
X
XOn the SGI 3-d workstations,
Xshould you wish to have a large text window to scan printed output, move
Xthe mouse pointer into the text window and click the center mouse button.
XUse the reverse procedure to regain a large graphics window, i.e.,
Xmove the mouse pointer into the graphics window
Xand click the center mouse button.
X
X\subsection{Running MGED on a Tektronix}
X
XTo run MGED on the tek4014 class of terminals one needs to have TWO
Xterminals - the graphics terminal (4014 or one which emulates a 4014) and
Xanother terminal to enter commands on.
X
XThe procedure is as follows:
X\begin{enumerate}
X\item login on the graphics terminal
X\item enter {\em tty} to find out which terminal number has been assigned
X\item  enter {\em sleep 32000} to put the graphics terminal in sleep mode
X\item  login on the other terminal
X\item  enter {\em mged file} to execute MGED
X\item  enter {\em tek} to select the tek4014 device processor
X\item  enter the tty value found in step 2.
X\item  perform editing
X\item  enter {\em q} to quit MGED
X\item  enter control-c on the graphics terminal to end the sleep mode
X\item  logout on both terminals
X\end{enumerate}
X
XSince there are no knobs or buttons on the tek4014 class of terminals, one
Xis forced to use the {\em press} and {\em knob} commands to emulate these
Xperipherals.
XOther commands which can/should be used are:
X
X\begin{tabular}{rl}
Xill     & put up a desired path \\
Xcenter  & slew the display \\
Xsize    & zoom the display \\
Xsed     & solid edit immediately
X\end{tabular}
X
XThe main force behind the writing of a driver for the tek4014 terminals
Xwas to allow the use of the Teletype 5620 terminals.
XThese graphic terminals have an internal processor and different windows
Xcan be set up which represent different terminals.
XHence two terminals are NOT necessary.
XThe use of the Teletype 5620 terminals is then the same as the procedure
Xoutlined above, except each window represents a terminal.
X
X\section{The Pop-Up Button Menu}
X
XThe default MGED faceplate is shown in Figure \ref{faceplate}.
XIf the BUTTON MENU area on the screen is selected with the mouse,
Xthen the pop-up button menu appears, as shown in Figure \ref{buttonmenu}.
XThis menu can be very useful in reducing the amount of hand motion
Xbetween the mouse and the button box.
X
X\section{Starting Your Model}
X
XModeling practices using MGED can be quite individual.  The following is a
Xsuggested modeling method to start with; you may end up developing your own
Xstyle as you become more familiar with MGED.
X
XFirst of all, decide how you want to represent your model, including the
Xamount of detail, types of solids and regions necessary.  Have an accurate
Xsketch or engineering drawing available, so that you can easily tranfer its
Xinformation into the types of primitive solids necessary to create your model.
XWhere possible it is recommended to start with a large block solid and
X``subtract'' pieces from it.  In this way you avoid errors with abutting
Xfaces of a collection of solids ``unioned'' together.
X
XNext the solids are created using the
X{\em make}, {\em cp}, {\em mirror} or {\em in}
Xcommands.  Depending on the complexity of the model, the solids may be
Xcreated in the desired location or created at the origin and later
Xtranslated to the desired location.  Creation at the origin provides
Xan opportunity to take advantage of possible symmetries in the geometry.
XOnce all the solids are finished it is time to create the region[s],
Xwhich will describe (to MGED) how to combine the solids to represent
Xthe model.
X
XThe region[s] are then given the desired item/air code (if this is
Xnecessary, otherwise leave it as the system default value), and material
Xcodes.  The regions are then put onto a group, usually for functionality only.
XA group has no operations as such (like union [u], intersection [+] or
Xdifference [-]) and is just a collection of objects for convenient naming
Xof a whole screen or collection of objects.
END-of-b.tex
