X\chapter{CREATING NEW OBJECTS}
X
X\section{Creating New Leaves (Solids/Primitives)}
X
XA family of commands exists to allow the user to
Xadd more actual solids (leaf nodes) to the model database.
XTo obtain a precise duplicate of an existing solid (presumably to be
Xchanged by a subsequent editing command), the copy ({\em cp}) command
Xcan be used.  It is important to note that the copy operation is
Xdifferent from creating an {\em instance} of an existing solid;
Xthere are occasions to use both operations.
XIf the precise configuration of the solid desired is not important, the
X{\em make} command can be used to create a stock prototype solid of the
Xdesired type with the given name, which can then be edited to suit.
XThe {\em mirror} command makes a
Xduplicate of an existing solid reflected about
Xone of the coordinate axes.
X
XIf the actual numeric parameters of a solid are known, then the {\em in}
Xcommand can be used.  In addition to prompting for the descriptions of
Xthe full generic primitive solids, this command also accepts
Xabbreviated input formats.  For example, a wedge or an RPP can be entered
Xwith a minimum of parameters, even though a database ARB8 is created.
XSimilarly, the parameters for a right circular cylinder can be given,
Xresulting in a truncated general cone (TGC) being stored.
XThis is not a very sophisticated way to build solids, but it receives
Xa surprising amount of use.
X
XA number of commands also exist to create new solids with some
Xhigher level description.  For example, the {\em inside} command
Xcreates a new solid inside an existing solid, separated from the
Xexisting solid by specified tolerances.  This is quite useful for
Xcreating hollow objects such as fuel tanks.
XIt is possible to create a plate with a specified
Xazimuthal orientation and fallback angle, or to create an ARB8 (plate)
Xby specifying three points and a thickness, or to create an ARB8
Xgiven one point, an azimuthal orientation, and a fallback angle.
X
X\section{Specific Cases}
X
XAfter having started MGED and created a new database, the next
Xstep is to use the {\em units} command to tell the system that you will
Xbe entering values in mm, cm, m, in or ft.  For our example we will
Xwork in mm:
X
X\begin{verbatim}
X     units mm
X\end{verbatim}
X
XNow you may give your database a title using the {\em title} command as in:
X
X\begin{verbatim}
X     title Mechanical Bracket
X\end{verbatim}
X
XThis title (``Mechanical Bracket'') now appears at bottom left hand
Xcorner of graphics window.  Further examples:
X\begin{verbatim}
X     title six wheeled tank
X     title stub axle
X\end{verbatim}
X
XAt this point you can start creating your solid objects using the ``arbs'',
X``sph'', ``tor'', {\em etc},
Xarguments to the {\em make} or {\em in} command.
XThe {\em make} command gives you a solid to a default size,
Xyou then have to use the
Xsolid edit mode to interactively edit the solid to the desired size.
X{\em make} command is entered as below:
XExamples:
X\begin{verbatim}
Xmake box arb8
Xmake cyl rcc
Xmake ball sph
X\end{verbatim}
XThe first argument is the solid name, and the second argument is
Xthe primitive type.
X
XThe {\em in} command expects you to key in a set of parameters to describe your
Xsolid; the parameters can be the x y and z of a vertex (such as the
Xcorner of an ARP8), or the x y and z of a vector (such as the height
Xor H vector of a BOX) or the radius (such as for a torus).
XBelow is a list of primitives
Xwith their {\em in} commands as requested by MGED and sample input.
XReading an {\em in} file into a MGED data file will be discussed later.
XNote how providing incomplete input to the {\em in} command will result
Xin MGED repeating the prompt for the missing information.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{ex.rpp.ps}
X\caption{Example RPP.}
X\label{ex.rpp}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{RPP (rectangular parallelepiped)}
X
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em in name rpp}\\
XEnter XMIN, XMAX, YMIN, YMAX, ZMIN, ZMAX: {\em 0 25} \\
XEnter YMIN, YMAX, ZMIN, ZMAX: {\em 0 50} \\
XEnter ZMIN, ZMAX: {\em 0 100} \\
X}
X
XThis sequence produces the RPP shown in Figure \ref{ex.rpp}.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{ex.box.ps}
X\caption{Example BOX.}
X\label{ex.box}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{BOX (BOX)}
X
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em in my box} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vertex: {\em 0 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vector H: {\em 25 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vector W: {\em 0 50 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vector D: {\em 0 0 100} \\
X}
XThis sequence produces the BOX shown in Figure \ref{ex.box}.
X
