X\section{Creating New Combinations}
X
XNon-terminal nodes in the directed acyclic graph stored in the database
Xare also called {\em combinations}.
XIt is possible to extend the definition of a non-terminal node by
Xadding an instance of an existing node to the non-terminal node
Xwith an associated boolean
Xoperation of union;  this is done by the {\em i}
X(instance) command.  To start with, such an instance has an identity
Xmatrix stored in the arc;  the user needs to separately edit the
Xarc to move the instance to some other location.
XIf the non-terminal node being extended does not exist, it is created first.
X
XThe instance command provides the simplest way to create a reference to
Xanother node.  Instances of a whole list of nodes can be added to a
Xnon-terminal node by way of the group {\em g} command.
XIf instances of a list of nodes with non-union boolean operations
Xis to be added to a non-terminal node, the region {\em r} command
Xaccepts a list of (operation, name) pairs, where the single lower case
Xcharacter ``u'' indicates union, ``--'' indicates subtraction, and
X``+'' indicates intersection.  The first operation specified
Xis not significant.  An example of this command might be:
X\begin{center}
X{\em r non-terminal u node1 -- node2 + node3}
X\end{center}
XFor historical reasons,
Xthere is no explicit grouping possible, occasionally forcing
Xthe user to create intermediate non-terminal nodes to allow the
Xrealization of the desired boolean formula.
XIt is also important to note that for the same reasons
Xthere is an {\em implicit} grouping between union terms, i.e.
X\begin{center}
Xu n1 -- n2 + n3 u n4 -- n5
X\end{center}
Xis evaluated as
X\begin{center}
X(n1 -- n2 + n3) union (n4 -- n5)
X\end{center}
Xrather than
X\begin{center}
X((((n1 -- n2) + n3) union n4) -- n5)
X\end{center}
XTherefore, you can think of the solids
Xon either side of the union operators as surrounded by parentheses.
XThe order of the region members is
Xcritical, and must be scrutinized when members are added or deleted from a
Xregion.
XThe order can be printed out using the {\em l} or {\em cat} commands.
