X\chapter{VIEWING FUNCTIONS}
X
XThe MGED viewing features are designed to allow one to examine an object
Xin close detail.  Any of the viewing features can be invoked at any time.
XIt should be noted, that these functions do not change the actual data,
Xonly the way the data is displayed.
X
X\section{Preset Views}
X
XSix standard views (front, rear, top, bottom, left, and right) and one
Xoblique view (azimuth 35, elevation 25 isometric) are each assigned to the
Xfunction buttons, views 35 25 (isometric), top, right, front,
X45 45 are available from the screen editor menu.  Hence, any of these views
Xis immediately available at the press of the appropriate function button or
Xmouse selection.  The views available are not limited to these standard views
Xhowever, as the display can be rotated to any view by using the dial box.  By
Xpressing the function button labeled ``save view'' or entering
Xthe keyboard {\em saveview} command, the present view as displayed display is
Xsaved (used for raytracing,
Xproducing colored pictures, which will be discussed later).
XAt any time, the saved view can be immediately returned to the
Xscreen by pressing the ``restore view'' function button.  The
X``restore view'' button will be lit whenever a view has been saved.
XThe function button labeled ``reset'',
Xrestores the display to the default view (front) when pressed.
X
X\section{View Translation}
X
XThe displays can be panned or slewed on the screen in two ways -- using the
Xmouse pointer or by using the dial box knobs.  When one is editing, the mouse
Xfunctions are not available for slewing, hence one must use the dial box knobs
Xto slew the display.
X
XTo slew the display using the control knobs, one uses the knobs labeled
X``slew x'' or ``slew y''.  The null positions on these knobs is in the
Xcenter or straight up.  If the ``slew x'' knob is turned clockwise of center,
Xthe display will move to the right.  If it turned counterclockwise, the
Xdisplay will move to the left.  For the ``slew y'' central knob, clockwise
Xof the center moves the display up and counterclockwise moves the display
Xdown.  The further these knobs are turned from center, the faster the display
Xmoves.
X
X\section{View Zooming}
X
XOne can zoom the display by using the dial box knob labeled ``zoom''.
XAgain the null position of this knob is center or straight
Xup.  Turning this knob clockwise of center causes the display to increase in
Xsize producing a zoom-in effect.  Turning this knob counterclockwise of center
Xcauses the display to decrease in size or zoom-out.  Again, the further the
X``zoom'' knob is turned from center, the faster the zooming will occur.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{adc.ps}
X\caption{The Angle Distance Cursor.}
X\label{adc}
X\end{figure}
X
X\section{The Angle Distance Cursor (ADC)}
X
XThe angle distance cursor is a construction aid used to measure
Xangles and distances. It should be noted that all measurements are
Xmade in the projected space of the screen, so one should measure only
Xin a view normal to the surface where the measurement is to take place.
XThe ADC is placed on (or removed from) the display by pushing the ``ADC''
Xbutton.
XThe ADC consists of three cursors which cover the entire screen.
XFigure \ref{adc} depicts the ADC as it appears on the screen.
XAll the cursors are centered at the same point and can be moved to any
Xlocation on the screen.  Two of these cursors rotate for angle measuring
Xpurposes. Angle cursor 1 is solid while angle cursor 2 is dashed.  Angle
Xcursor 1 has movable tic marks for measuring distances on the screen.
XThe two angle cursors move with the horizontal and vertical
Xlines of the main cursor.
XThe resulting effect is the moving of the center point
Xhorizontally or vertically.
XThe ADC is controlled by the bottom row
Xof the (Megatek) knobs:
X
X\begin{tabular}{rl}
XKnob  & Function \\
X \\
X6     & moves the center in the horizontal direction \\
X7     & moves the center in the vertical direction \\
X8     & rotates angle cursor 1  (alpha) \\
X9     & rotates angle cursor 2  (beta) \\
X10    & moves the tic marks
X\end{tabular}
X
XWhenever the ADC is on the screen, there is a readout at the bottom of
Xthe screen listing pertinent information about the ADC.
XThis information includes the angles that angle cursors 1 and 2
Xhave been rotated (alpha and beta), the distance the tic marks are
Xfrom the center of the ADC, and the location of the center of the ADC.
XThis information is continually updated on the screen.
X
X\chapter{MGED EDITING FEATURES}
X
XThe heart of the MGED system is its editing features.
XThe editing features are divided into two classes: object editing
Xand solid editing.
XObject editing is designed to allow one to change the location,
Xsize, and orientation of an object.
XRecall that an object is defined as the basic data unit of the
XMGED system and includes both combinations and solids.
XIn the case of a solid, one needs to change not only its location,
Xsize, and orientation, but also its ``shape''.
XChanging the shape of a solid means changing any of its individual parameters.
XHence, solid editing is handled separately.
X
X\section{Combination Editing (OBJECT EDIT)}
X
XBefore being able to enter the OBJECT EDIT state
X(i.e. edit non-terminal),
Xit is necessary to pass through two intermediate states
Xin which the full path of an object to be edited is specified,
Xand the location of one arc along that path is designated for editing.
XIt is possible to create a transformation matrix to be applied
Xabove the root of the tree, affecting everything in the path,
Xor to apply the matrix between any pair of nodes.
XFor example, if the full path /car/chassis/door is specified,
Xthe matrix could be applied above the node ``car'', between
X``car/chassis'', or between ``chassis/door''.
X
XThe transformation matrix to be applied at the
Xdesignated location can be created by the concatenation of
Xoperations, each specified through several types of user direction.
XTrees can be rotated around the center of the viewing cube;
Xthis rotation can be specified in degrees via keyboard command, or can
Xbe controlled by the rotation of a set of control dials or motions on
Xa three-axis joystick.
XTranslation of trees can be specified in terms of a precise new location
Xvia keyboard command, or by adjusting a set of control dials.
XTree translation can also be accomplished by pointing and
Xclicking with the mouse or tablet.
XUniform and single-axis (affine) scaling of a tree can be controlled
Xby a numeric scale factor via keyboard command, or by way of repeated
Xanalog scaling by pointing and clicking with the mouse or tablet.
XBefore we discuss the editing features of MGED, we will discuss
Xhow one selects objects for editing.
X
X\section{Selecting Objects For Editing}
X
XTo select a displayed object for editing, press the object illuminate button
Xor select ``Object illum'' from the ***BUTTON MENU***.
XThe object selection is a two step process.
X
XWhenever an object is displayed (using the {\em e} command), all paths in the
Xobject's hierarchy are traversed recursively, accumulating the transformation
Xmatrices.  When the bottom of the path (a solid) is encountered, the
Xaccumulated
Xtransformations are applied to the solid's parameters and the solid is drawn.
XThus every solid displayed is really a path ending with that solid.
XIf the object has been displayed using the {\em E} command, the same procedure
Xis followed, but only until a region is encountered.
XThen all members of the region have the accumulated transformations
Xapplied and the region is then ``evaluated'' and drawn.
X
XIn the first step of the object selection process, the path is selected.
XAgain, the data tablet is divided in as many horizontal sections as there are
Xpaths drawn.
XThe path (solid or evaluated region) corresponding to the horizontal
Xsection the pen/mouse is located in will be illuminated (brighter on B/W
Xdisplays and white on color displays).
XThis complete path is also listed on the display.
XWhen the pen/mouse is pressed the illuminated path is selected.
X
XIn the second step, a member of the selected path is chosen.
XAll editing will then be applied to this member.
XThe tablet is divided into as many horizontal sections as there are
Xpath members.
XThe word ``[MATRIX]'' is used to illuminate path members and will appear
Xabove the member corresponding to the location of the pen/mouse.
XPressing the pen/mouse when the desired path member is ``illuminated''
Xwill put MGED in the object edit state.
XThe editing will be performed on the path member selected.
X
XIf a solid is located at the bottom of this path, it becomes the key
Xsolid and its vertex becomes the key point.
XIf an evaluated region is at the bottom of the path, the center of
Xthis region becomes the key point.
XAll object editing is done with respect to this key point.
X
XThe object editing features can be invoked in any order and at any time
Xonce an object has been selected for editing.  During object editing, any of
Xthe viewing features, such as changing views, zooming, and slewing, can be
Xused, and in fact, are usually quite useful.  Again, the only way to exit the
Xobject editing mode is to ``accept'' or ``reject'' the editing.
XIf the ``reject'' button is pressed (or selected from the edit menu), the
Xobject will return to its pre-edit state.  If the ``accept'' button is pressed
X(or selected from the edit menu), the data base will be changed to reflect the
Xobject editing performed.
X
X\section{Object Edit State}
X
XWhen MGED enters the object edit state, the following occurs:
X
X\begin{enumerate}
X\item all the solids/evaluated regions of the edited object
Xbecome illuminated
X\item the key solid's parameters are labeled  OR \\
Xthe center of the key evaluated region is marked
X\item the key solid's parameters are listed and
Xcontinually updated  OR \\
Xthe key evaluated region's center is listed and
Xcontinually updated
X\item the ***OBJ EDIT*** menu is displayed
X\end{enumerate}
X
X\section{Translate An Object}
X
XThere are three ways to translate an object:  translate in the screen
XX direction only (X move), translate in the screen Y direction only
X(Y move) or just straight translation (XY move).
XIn all cases, the complete object is translated so that the ``key point''
Xis positioned at the desired location.
XThe {\em translate} command is used to enter a precise location (x,y,z) for
Xthe key point.
XEntering {\em translate x y z} will move the complete object so that the key
Xpoint will be at coordinates (x,y,z).
X
X\section{Rotate An Object}
X
XRotation of the object may be accomplished by selecting the ``Rotate''
Xmenu item, or pressing the ``Rotate'' button.
XTurning the knobs results in the object being rotated.
XThe {\em rotobj x y z} command can be used here, to specify
Xa precise rotation in degrees.
XWhile in this edit state, the only way to rotate view is to use
Xthe {\em vrot x y z} command.
X
X\section{Scale An Object}
X\subsection{Global Scale}
X
XTo select global object scale, press the object scale button or select
X``Scale'' from the ***OBJ EDIT*** menu.
XWhen the pen/mouse is pressed, the edited object is scaled about the key
Xpoint by an amount
Xproportional to the distance the pen/mouse is from the center of the screen.
XIf the pen/mouse is above the center, the edited object will become larger.
XIf it is below the center, the object will become smaller.
XThe {\em scale} command can be used to enter precise scale factors.
XThe value entered is applied to the object as it existed when object
Xscale was entered.
XHence entering {\em scale 1} will return the object to its size when the
Xobject scale session first started.
X
X\subsection{Local Scale}
X
XLocal object scaling is allowed about any of the coordinate axes.
XTo select local scaling, press one of the buttons (OBJ Scale X, OBJ Scale Y,
Xor OBJ Scale Z) or select ``Scale X'', ``Scale Y'', or ``Scale Z'' from
Xthe ***OBJ EDIT*** menu.
XWhen the pen/mouse is pressed, the edited object is scaled in the selected
Xcoordinate axis only, about the key point.
XThe amount of scaling is proportional to the distance the pen/mouse is
Xfrom the center of the screen.
XIf the pen/mouse is above the center, the edited object will become larger
Xin the selected axis direction.
XIf it is below the center, the object will become smaller in the selected
Xaxis direction.
XThe {\em scale} command can be used to enter precise scale factors.
XThe value entered is applied to the object as it existed when local object
Xscale was entered.
XHence entering {\em scale 1} will return the object (in the selected axis
Xdirection) to its size when the object scale session first started.
X
X\section{Solid Editing}
X
XThere are two classes of editing operations that can be performed on
Xleaf nodes, the primitive solids.
XThe first class of operations are generic operations which can be applied to
Xany type of solid, and the second class of operations are those operations
Xwhich are specific to a particular type of solid.
XGeneric operations which can be applied to all primitive solids are
Xrotation, translation and scaling.
XRecall that primitives can be treated as any other object and ``object
Xedited'' as detailed above.
XEach primitive solid also has a variety of editing operations available that
Xare specific to the definition of that solid.  These operations are
Xdetailed below.
X
XThe solid editing mode is necessary to
Xperform to basic shapes of solids.
XPrecise modifications
Xof the shape are possible (using the {\em p} keyboard command) in the solid
Xediting mode.
X
XThe solid editing feature allows the user to interactively translate,
Xrotate, scale, and modify individual parameters of a solid.  Whenever one is
Xin the solid edit mode, the parameters of the solid being edited are listed
Xand continually updated at the top of the screen.  Certain parameters are
Xalso labeled on the solid being edited.  Solid editing  is generally used to
X``build'' objects by producing solids of the desired shape and size in the
Xcorrect orientation and position.  Once the object is built, object editing
Xis used to scale, orient, and position the object in the description.  The
Xgeneral philosophy of solid editing is to first create a solid with the
Xdesired name and then to edit this solid.  As an example, suppose one were
Xto build an object called ``BRACKET''; to produce the base of the object the
Xprimitive solid type ARB8 (see Figure 1) would be used along with either the
X{\em in} command or {\em make} command, so one would type:
X\begin{verse}
X     in btm box 0 0 0  0 -90 0  40 0 0  0 0 6 \\
X     make block arb8
X\end{verse}
XA new solid called ``btm'' or ``block'' would be created and displayed on the
Xscreen.  These solids would then be edited using solid editing to produce the
Xsolid parameters for the shape desired.
X
X\section{Selecting Solids For Editing}
X
XThe procedure for solid editing is quite similar to that for object editing.
XFirst, solid edit state must be entered, by pressing the
X``solid illuminate'' button, or selecting the ``solid illum'' menu item.
XSecond,
XA solid is selected for
Xediting using the illuminate mode, just as in object editing,
Xby moving the cursor up and down, and choosing the desired solid.
XThe solid data is listed at the top of the screen and a
Xheader depending on the solid type is written above the solid editing data.
XThird, select the appropriate function button or edit menu operations,
Xand perform the editing desired.  Finally, the solid
Xediting mode is exited
Xby either accepting or rejecting the editing performed.
X
XA solid must be displayed before it can be picked for editing.
XTo pick a displayed solid for editing, press the ``solid illum'' button or
Xselect ``Solid Illum'' from the ***BUTTON MENU***.
XThe data tablet and pen/mouse are then used to pick the solid.
XThe surface of the data tablet is divided into as many horizontal sections
Xas there are solids displayed.
XThe displayed solid corresponding to the horizontal section the pen/mouse
Xis located in will be ``illuminated'' (it will become brighter on black and
Xwhite devices and white on color devices).
XThe complete hierarchical path to reach the solid is also listed on the
Xdisplay.  When the pen/mouse is pressed, MGED enters the solid edit state
Xwith the illuminated solid as the solid to be edited.
XIf the solid is not multiply referenced, entering {\em sed solidname} on
Xthe keyboard will immediately put MGED in the solid edit state with
X{\em solidname} as the edited solid.
X
X\section{Solid Edit State}
X
XWhen MGED enters the solid edit state, the following occurs:
X
X\begin{enumerate}
X\item the edited solid remains illuminated
X\item the edited solid's parameters are labeled
X\item the edited solid's parameters are listed
X\item  (and continually updated)
X\item the ***SOLID EDIT*** menu is displayed
X\item the parameter edit menu is initially displayed (default)
X\end{enumerate}
X
X\section{Rotate A Solid}
X
XSolid rotation allows the user to rotate the solid being edited to any
Xdesired orientation.  The rotation is performed about the vertex of the
Xsolid.  To select this option, one presses the function button labeled
X``solid rotate'' or selects from the edit menu on screen.
XThe rotation can be done using the dial box or one can input exact angles
Xof rotation of the solid by using the {\em p} keyboard command.
XFor example, typing:
X{\em \center
Xp alpha beta gamma
X}
Xwill rotate the solid {\em alpha} degrees about the x-axis, {\em beta} degrees
Xabout the y-axis and {\em gamma} degrees about the z-axis.  Alpha, beta, and
Xgamma are measured from the original ``zero'' orientation of the solid,
Xdefined when the ``solid edit'' function button was
Xpressed.  Hence, typing
X{\em \center
Xp 0 0 0
X}
Xwill always return the solid to its original position (its position when the
Xcurrent solid editing session began) before accepting edit.
X
XTo select solid rotation, press the solid rotate button or select ``Rotate''
Xfrom the ***SOLID EDIT*** menu.
XThe joy stick or appropriate rotation knobs then will rotate the edited solid
Xabout the coordinate axes.
XThe solid is rotated about its vertex.
XThe parameter (p) command can be used to make precise rotation changes.
XThe values entered after the p are absolute -- the rotations are applied
Xto the solid as it existed when solid rotation was first selected.
XThus entering {\em p 0 0 0} will ``undo'' any rotations performed since
Xsolid rotation was selected.
XThe rotation about the z-axis is done first, then the y, then the x.
X
X\section{Translate A Solid}
X
XSolid translation allows the user to place the solid being edited anywhere
Xin the description.  To invoke this option, one presses the function
Xbutton labeled ``solid trans'' or selects from the screen edit
Xmenu.  To move the solid, use the mouse pointer to position the solid and
Xclick the center mouse button.  Whenever the mouse button is pressed, the
XVERTEX of the solid moves to that location on the screen.
X
XOne can read the actual coordinates of the vertex on the top of the
Xscreen, along with other data.  If the actual desired coordinates of the
Xvertex are known, one can place the solid exactly using the {\em p} keyboard
Xcommand.  For example, to place a solid's vertex at the coordinates (x,y,z)
Xone would type:
X{\em \center
Xp40 20 10
X}
XThe solid would then jump to this location.
X
XTo select solid translation, press the solid translate button or
Xselect ``Translate'' from the ***SOLID EDIT*** menu.
XWhen the pen/mouse is pressed, the vertex of the edited solid will
Xmove to that location.
XThe parameter (p) command can be used to translate the solid to
Xa precise location.
XEntering {\em p x y z} will place the vertex of the edited solid at (x, y, z).
X
X\section{Scale A Solid}
X
XThe solid SCALE feature allows the user to scale the solid being to any
Xdesirable size.  The scaling is done about the vertex of the solid, hence NO
Xtranslation of the solid occurs.  The scaling is performed using the mouse
Xpointer and clicking the center mouse button, just as in object scaling.  One
Xcan input an exact scale factor using the {\em p} keyboard command, in the form
Xof.  For example, typing
X{\em \center
Xp factor
X}
Xwill scale the solid by an amount equal to {\em factor}.   The value of
X{\em factor} is absolute -- the original solid is scaled.  By setting {\em factor}
Xequal to one (1), the original size solid will be displayed on the screen
Xbefore accepting your edit.
X
XTo select solid scale, press the solid scale button or select ``Scale''
Xfrom the ***SOLID EDIT*** menu.
XWhen the pen/mouse is pressed, the edited solid is scaled by an amount
Xproportional to the distance the pen/mouse is from the center of the screen.
XIf the pen/mouse is above the center, the edited solid will become larger.
XIf it is below the center, the solid will become smaller.
XThe parameter (p) command can be used to enter precise scale factors.
XThe value entered is applied to the solid as it existed when solid
Xscale was entered.
XHence entering {\em p 1} will return the solid to its size when solid scale
Xsession first started.
X
X\section{Solid Parameter Editing}
X
XTo modify individual solid parameters, press the menu button or select
X``edit menu'' from the ***SOLID EDIT*** menu.
XA menu listing what parameter editing is available for that particular
Xsolid type will be displayed.
XUsing the pen/mouse select the desired item(s) from this menu.
XFor most of the parameter editing, the {\em p} command can be used to
Xmake precise changes.
XParameter editing is the default edit mode entered when MGED first
Xenters the solid edit state.
XIn the following paragraphs, we will discuss parameter editing
Xfor each of the MGED general types of solids.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{menu-arb-ctl.ps}
X\caption{ARB Control Menu.}
X\label{menu-arb-ctl}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{ARB Parameter Editing}
X
XThe GENERAL ARB class of solids represents all the convex polyhedrons
X(RPP, BOX, RAW, and ARBs).
XThe ARBs comprise five classes of polyhedrons each with a characteristic
Xnumber of vertices.
XThese are the ARB8, ARB7, ARB6, ARB5, and ARB4, where the ARB8 has
Xeight vertices, etc.
XDuring editing, all the vertices are labeled on the screen.
X
XAn ARB is defined by a fixed number of vertices where all faces must
Xbe planar.  This fact means that during parameter editing, movement
Xof individual vertices in faces containing four vertices is not allowed.
XThere are three classes of parameter editing that can be done to ARBs:
Xmove edges,
Xmove faces, and rotate faces.  There is an ``ARB control menu''
X(see Figure \ref{menu-arb-ctl}) from
Xwhich one selects the type of parameter editing to be done.
XA specific ARB edit menu will appear dependent on which parameter editing
Xoption was selected.  The ``return'' entry on each of these specific menus
Xwill return the ``ARB control'' menu to the screen.
X
XNote that there are several keyboard commands that apply only to ARB solids
Xwhich are being edited in SOLID EDIT state.
XOnce such command is {\em mirface}, which replaces a designated
Xface of the ARB with a copy of an original face mirrored about
Xthe indicated axis.
XAnother such command is {\em extrude}, which projects a designated face
Xa given amount in the indicated direction.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{menu-arb8-edge.ps}
X\caption{Move Edge Menu for ARB8.}
X\label{menu-arb8-edge}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{menu-arb4-edge.ps}
X\caption{Move Edge Menu for ARB4.}
X\label{menu-arb4-edge}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{menu-arb8-face.ps}
X\caption{Move Face Menu for ARB8.}
X\label{menu-arb8-face}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{menu-arb4-face.ps}
X\caption{Move Face Menu for ARB4.}
X\label{menu-arb4-face}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{Move ARB Edges}
X
XTo move an ARB edge, select the desired edge from the ``move edge'' menu.
XFor example, Figure \ref{menu-arb8-edge} shows the menu for
Xmoving an edge of an ARB8, and Figure \ref{menu-arb4-edge}
Xshows the menu for moving an edge of an ARB4.
XA point is then ``input'' either through a pen press or through the {\em p}
Xcommand.
XThe line containing the selected edge is moved so that it goes through
Xcoordinate of the input point.
XAny affected faces are automatically adjusted to remain planar.
X
X\subsection{Move ARB Faces}
X
XTo move an ARB face, select the desired face from the ``move face'' menu.
XA point is then ``input'' either through a pen press or through the {\em p}
Xcommand.  The plane containing the edited face is then moved so that it
Xcontains the input point.  The new face is then calculated and the ARB
Xis displayed.
XThe move face menus for an ARB8 are shown
Xin Figure \ref{menu-arb8-face}, and the move face menus for an ARB4
Xare shown in Figure \ref{menu-arb4-face}.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{menu-arb8-rot.ps}
X\caption{Rotate Face Menu for ARB8.}
X\label{menu-arb8-rot}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{menu-arb4-rot.ps}
X\caption{Rotate Face Menu for ARB4.}
X\label{menu-arb4-rot}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{Rotate ARB Faces}
X
XARB faces may be rotated around any of the vertices comprising that face.
XFirst, select the desired face from the ``rotate face'' menu.  You will then
Xbe asked to select the vertex number around which to rotate the face.
XThe face can be rotated about the three coordinate axes.  The knobs (Rotate X,
XRotate Y, and Rotate Z) are used for this purpose.  For precise rotations,
Xuse the {\em p} command.  If three values are entered after the {\em p}, then
Xthey are interpreted as angles (absolute) of rotation about the X, Y, Z axes
Xrespectively.  If only two values are entered, then they are considered as
Xrotation and fallback angles for the normal to that face.  The {\em eqn}
Xcommand can also be used here to define the plane equation coefficients of
Xthe face being rotated.
XThe rotate face menus for an ARB8 are shown
Xin Figure \ref{menu-arb8-rot}, and the rotate face menus for an ARB4
Xare shown in Figure \ref{menu-arb4-rot}.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{ped-tgc.ps}
X\caption{Typical TGC During Parameter Editing.}
X\label{ped-tgc}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{Truncated General Cone (TGC) Parameter Editing}
X
XThe TGC general class of solids includes all the cylindrical COMGEOM solids.
XThe defining parameters of the TGC are two base vectors (A and B), a height
Xvector (H), two top vectors (C and D), and the vertex (V).
XThe top vectors C and D are directed the same as the base vectors A and
XB respectively,
Xhence the top vectors are defined only by their lengths (c and d).
XDuring solid editing, only vectors A and B are
Xlabeled on the display.
XFigure \ref{ped-tgc} depicts a typical TGC during parameter editing.
X
XIt is possible to change the length of the H, A, B, C, or D
Xvectors, resulting in a change in height or eccentricity of the
Xend plates.  The overall size of the A,B or C,D end plates can
Xbe adjusted, or the size of both can be changed together, leaving
Xonly the H vector constant.
XThe H vector or the base plate (AXB) can be rotated.
XRecall that vectors A \& C and vectors B \& D have like directions, hence
Xrotating the base (AXC) will automatically rotate the top (BXD).
XFinally, one can move the end of the height vector H
Xwith the TGC becoming or remaining
Xa right cylinder (move end H (rt)),
Xor with the orientation of the base (and top)
Xunchanged (move end H).
XEither the mouse/tablet or the {\em p} command can be used.
XThese functions are selected from the menu which can be seen
Xin Figure \ref{ped-tgc}.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{ped-ell}
X\caption{Ellipsoid Parameter Editing Menu.}
X\label{ped-ell}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{Ellipsoid Parameter Editing}
X
XThe ELLG general class represents all the ellipsoidal solids, including
Xspheres and ellipsoids of revolution.
XThe defining parameters of the ELLG are three mutually perpendicular
Xvectors (A, B, and C) and the vertex (V).
XWhen an ELLG is being edited, only vectors A and B are labeled on the display.
XFigure \ref{ped-ell} depicts a typical ELLG during parameter editing.
X
XThe parameter editing of the ELLG consists of scaling the lengths of the
Xindividual vectors A, B, C.
XOne may also scale all theses vectors together of equal length.
X
XThe scaling of these vectors is done using the data tablet/mouse in
Xexactly the same manner as in object scaling.
XThe {\em p} keyboard command again can be used to produce a vector of
Xdesired length.
X
X\begin{figure}
