X\section{Copy Object}
X
X{\em \center cp oldobj newobj}
X
XThis command is used to produce a copy of an object (solid or comb).
XIn this case, the
Xobject "oldobj" will be copied into an object called "newobj".
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X              cp arb8 hullbot.s \\
X              cp tgc wheelrim.s \\
X              cp torso.r driver\_torso \\
X              cp proto.man driver \\
X}
X
X\section{Zap Screen}
X
X{\em \center Z}
X
XThis is the Zap command.  It clears all objects from the screen.
X
X\section{Drop objects from display screen}
X
X{\em \center d obj1 obj2 ... objn}
X
XThis command allows one to remove objects from the display screen.  In
Xthis case "obj1" thru "objn" will be removed from the display.
X
X\section{Move (rename) object}
X
X{\em \center mv old new}
X
XThis command is used to rename objects in the data file.  In this
Xcase, the object "old" will be renamed "new".
XA note of caution:  the name is changed only in the object record itself, not
Xin any member records.  Thus if the object "old" appears as a member
Xof any other object, the name will not be changed there.
XTo rename all occurrences of an object, use the "mvall" command.
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X              mv test hull \\
X              mv g00 air \\
X              mv g1 turret \\
X}
X
X\section{Set Local Working Units}
X
X{\em \center units ab}
X
XThis command allows one to change the local or working units at ANY time.
XThe only allowable values for "ab" are "mm", "cm", "m", "in", or "ft".
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X           units mm \\
X           units in \\
X}
X
X\section{Group objects}
X
X{\em \center g group obj1 obj2 ..... objn}
X
XThis command creates or appends to a combination record and
Xis used to group objects together either for editing or displaying
Xpurposes.  In this case, "obj1" through "objn" are added as members
Xto the combination "group".  If "group" does not exist, it is
Xcreated and "obj1" through "objn" are added as members.
XNOTE: no checking to see if "obji" is already a member of "group".
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X            g shell hull turret \\
X            g tank wheels engine crew shell \\
X            g tank track \\
X}
X
X\section{Create Region}
X
X{\em \center
Xr region op1 sol1 op2 sol2 .... opn soln
X}
X
XThis command is used to create regions or append to regions.
XIf "region" exists, then solids "sol1" through "soln" are
Xadded as members with "op1" through "opn" as the defining operations.
XIf "region" does not exist, then it is created and solids "sol1" through
X"soln" are added as members with "op1" through "opn" as the
Xdefining operations.  A region is merely a combination
Xrecord with a flag set and is distinguished from other combinations (groups)
Xsince it has meaning to the COMGEOM solid modeling system.
XNote that "+" or "u" must be the first operations in a region.
X
XWhen a region is created, the item and air codes are set equal to default values.
XIf the "regdef" command has been used, then those values will be used,
Xotherwise the values "1000 0 100 1" will be used respectively.
XTo change
Xthe item and air codes use the "item" command.
XThe "edcodes" command is probably the easiest and fastest way to change these
Xidentifing codes.
XNote:  In the past, all members of a region had to be solids, but
Xrecently combinations have been allowed as members of regions.  Hence,
Xthe names "soli" can also be combinations (groups) now.
XAlso, as in grouping, no checking for members already in a region.
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X             r hulltop.r + hulltop.s -- hullleft.s -- hullright.s \\
X             r gun + gun.s -- gunin.s \\
X             r gunair + gunin.s \\
X}
X
X\section{Instance an object}
X
X{\em \center
Xi object combname
X}
X
XThis command is used to make an instance of an object.
XAn instance of an object is produced by creating a combination
Xand making the object a member.
XIn this case, an instance of "object" is made by
Xcreating the combination record "combname" (if "combname" does not
Xalready exist) and adding "object" as a member.
XIf "combname" already exists, then "object" is added as the next member.
X
XAn instance is used to refer to an object, without making actual copies
Xof the object.  Instances are useful when one is adding a certain
Xcomponent to a target description many times.
XFurthermore, any modifications to an object which has been instanced need only be
Xdone in the original (prototype) object.
XThese modifications will then be automatically reflected in all the
Xinstances of the object.
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X                i heround he1 .he1. \\
X                i heround he2 .he2. \\
X                i heat heat1 .heat1. \\
X                i heat heat2 .heat2. \\
X}
X
X\section{Change Title of Database}
X
X{\em \center
Xtitle newtitle
X}
X
XThis command allows one to change the title of the model database at any time.
XThe string "newtitle" will become the new title, and may contain blanks.
XThe title is limited to 72 characters including blanks.
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X          title XM89A -- New version of tank \\
X          title M345 (groups are m345 and m345a) \\
X}
X
X\section{Extrude}
X
X{\em \center
Xextrude \#\#\#\# distance
X}
X
XThis command allows the user to project
Xa face(\#\#\#\#) of an arb being edited a normal distance to create a new arb.
XThe value of "face" is 4 digits such as 1256. If the face is projected
Xin the wrong direction use a negative "distance".
XOne common use for this command is
Xfor producing armor plates of a desired thickness.
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X              extrude 1234 20 \\
X              extrude 2367 34.75 \\
X              extrude 2367 -34.75 \\
X}
X
X\section{Remove members from Combination}
X
X{\em \center
Xrm comb mem1 mem2 .... memN
X}
X
XThis command allows one to delete members from a combination (group or region) record.
XIn this case, members "mem1" through "memn" will be deleted from
Xthe combination "comb".
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X              rm tank hull wheels \\
X              rm region1 solid8 solid112 \\
X              rm turtop.r tursidel.s tursider.s  \\
X}
X
X\section{List Object Information}
X
X{\em \center
Xl object
X}
X
XThis command is used to list information about objects in the data file.
XThe information listed depends on what type of record "object" is.
XIf "object" is a combination record, then the members are listed.
XIf "object" is a solid record, then the MGED general solid type and
Xthe parameters as presently in the data file are listed.
XNote:  only the solid parameters as they exist in the solid record are
Xlisted, no transformation matrix is applied.
XHence, if the solid was edited as a member of a combination, the "l"
Xcommand will not reflect the editing in the listed parameters.
XTo produce this type of listing, see the "listeval" command.
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X               l hull \\
X               l turret \\
X               l turtop.s \\
X               l arb8 \\
X}
X
X\section{Analyze Solid}
X
X{\em \center
Xanalyze solid
X}
X
XThis command produces information about a solid (all except ARS).
XThe information includes surface area(s) and volume.
XAlso, in the case of ARBs, edge lengths and rot and fallback angles
Xand plane equations are given for each face.
XIf "solid" is present that solid name will be used and analyzed.
XIf "solid" is absent, the solid at the bottom of the present path
Xbeing edited will be analyzed.
X
X\section{Mirror Object}
X
X{\em \center
Xmirror oldobj newobj axis
X}
X
XThis command is used to create a new object which is
Xthe mirror image of an existing object about an axis.
XThe object may be either a solid or a combination.
XIn this case, a mirror image of the object "oldobj" will created
Xabout the axis indicated by "axis" and the new object record will
Xbe called "newobj".
XThe only acceptable values for the parameter "axis" are "x", "y", and "z".
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X              mirror tur.left.s tur.right.s y
X              mirror tur.top.s tur.bot.s z
X              mirror tur.front.s tur.back.s x
X              mirror lt\_gun rt\_gun y
X}
X
X\section{Create ARB8}
X
X{\em \center
Xarb name rot fb
X}
X
XThis command allows one to create an arb8
Xwith the desired rotation and fallback angles.
XIn this case, an arb8 with the name of "name" will be created with the desired
Xrotation angle of "rot" degrees and the fallback angle of "fb" degrees.
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X           arb top1.s 0 90 \\
X           arb sidelt.s 90 0 \\
X           arb upglacis.s 0 60 \\
X}
X
X\section{Change Item (Ident) and Air codes of Region}
X
X{\em \center
Xitem region ident air
X}
X
XThis command allows one to change the item or
Xair code numbers of a region.  If the air code ("air") is not included,
Xa zero is assumed.
XTo change the air code, a zero item code must be used (see second
Xexample below).
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X            item region1 105 \\
X            item region7 0 2 \\
X            item region11 129 0 \\
X}
X
X\section{Specify Material Properties}
X
X{\em \center
Xmater comb [material]
X}
X
XThis command is used to change the material properties specification for
Xa combination.
X
X\section{Edit Combination Record Info}
X
X{\em \center
Xedcomb comb regionflag regionid air los GIFTmater
X}
X
XThis command is used to change the material and the los percent for
Xa region.
X
X\section{Edit (Display) an object on the screen}
X
X{\em \center
Xe obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command allows one to display objects on the screen.
XIn this case, "obj1" thru "objn" will be displayed on the screen.
X
X\section{Evaluated Display of Object on the screen}
X
X{\em \center
XE obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command is the same as the "e" command, except the regions will
Xbe evaluated before being displayed.
X
X\section{Zap screen and Display Object}
X
X{\em \center
XB obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command is the same as the "e" command, except that the screen
Xis cleared (Zap) before the objects are displayed.
X
X\section{Kill (delete) object from database}
X
X{\em \center
Xkill obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command allows one to remove objects from the file itself.
XOnly the object records themselves are removed, any references made
Xto these objects still will exist.
XTo remove the references also, see the "killall" command.
X
X\section{List Table of Contents}
X
X{\em \center
Xt obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis is the table of contents command.  If arguments are present, a list
Xof all objects in the file matching these names will be printed.
XIf there are no arguments, then a listing of all objects will be printed.
X
X\section{List Tree Tops}
X
X{\em \center
Xtops
X}
X
XThis command will search the target file hierarchy, and list all "top level"
Xobjects (objects which are not members of any other object).
XThis command is useful to make sure objects have been grouped properly.
X
X\section{Make prototypical solid}
X
X{\em \center
Xmake name type
X}
X
XThis command will create a solid of a specified type.
XThis solid will be named "name" and the solid type will be "type".
XThe acceptable types are: arb8, arb7, arb6, arb5, arb4, tor, tgc, tec,
Xrec, trc, rcc, ellg, ell, sph.
XThis new solid will be drawn at the center of the screen.
XThis command should be used to create
Xsolids for editing.
X
X\section{Mirror ARB Face}
X
X{\em \center
Xmirface \#\#\#\# axis
X}
X
XThis command allows one to mirror a face of an edited arb about an axis.
XThis command is quite useful for adding air to a "symmetric" target.
X
X\section{Print Summary of Objects}
X
X{\em \center
Xsummary s|r|g
X}
X
XThis command will produce a summary of objects in the target file.
XIf the options s, r, or g are entered a listing of the solids, regions,
Xor groups will also be presented.
X
X\section{Specify Numeric Parameter(s)}
X
X{\em \center
Xp dx [dy dz]
X}
X
XThis is the parameter modification command and is used during solid
Xediting to make precise changes.
XThe actual meaning of the values typed after the "p", depend on what
Xediting option is being performed.
XIf one were translating a solid, then the values would be the x,y,z
Xcoordinates of the vertex of the solid.
X
X\section{Release Current Display}
X
X{\em \center
Xrelease
X}
XThis command releases the current display device,
Xand attaches the null device.
X
X\section{Attach to Display Device}
X
X{\em \center
Xattach device
X}
X
XThis command allows one to attach a display device (the present display device
Xis released first).
XThe present acceptable values for "device" are vg, mg, tek, rat, plot, tek4109, ir, sgi, and nu.
XThe "plot" device will produce a UNIX-plot of the present view (including the
Xfaceplate) on a display device using a specific filter.
XYou will be asked which filter to use.
XSample filters include "tplot" and "plot-fb".
X
X\section{Numeric Object Rotation Edit}
X
X{\em \center
Xrotobj xdeg ydeg zdeg
X}
X
XThis command allows one to make precise rotations of an object during
Xobject editing.
XMGED must be in the "object edit" state for this command to have effect.
XIf "object rotation" is not in effect, MGED will select this option for you
Xand perform the rotation.
XThe object will be rotated "xdeg" about the x-axis, "ydeg" about the
Xy-axis, and "zdeg" about the z-axis.
XThe rotation is "absolute"....the total rotation since the beginning
Xof object editing will be equal to the input values.
XThe rotation is done about the "KEY" point for the object being edited.
X
X\section{Scale Edited Object}
X
X{\em \center
Xscale xxx.xx
X}
X
XThis command allows one to make precise scaling changes to an object
Xduring object editing.
XMGED must be in the "object edit" state for this command to have effect.
XIf one of the object scale options is not in effect, the "global scale"
Xoptions will be selected.
XThe object will be scaled by a TOTAL amount equal to the input value.
XIf one of the local scale options is in effect, the object will be
Xscaled in the selected axis direction by an amount equal to the input value.
XThe scaling is done about the "KEY" point of the object being edited.
X
X\section{Translate Edited Object}
X
X{\em \center
Xtranslate xxx.xx yyy.yy zzz.zz
X}
X
XThis command allows one to make precise translation changes to an object
Xduring object editing.
XMGED must be in the "object edit" state for this command to have effect.
XIf the object translation option is not in effect, this option will be
Xselected and the translation performed.
XThe "KEY" point of the object being edited will move to the input coordinates.
X
X\section{Fix Broken Hardware (sometimes)}
X
X{\em \center
Xfix
X}
X
XThis command will "fix" (restart) the display device after a hardware error.
X
X\section{Ray-Trace Current View}
X
X{\em \center
Xrt [-s\#]
X}
X
XThis command will run the {\bf rt}(1) program
Xto produce a color shaded iamge of objects on the currently
Xselected framebuffer.
XThe resolution of the iamge (number of rays) is equal to "\#" from the "-s"
X(square view resolution) option.
XIf the -s option is absent, 50x50 ray resolution will be used.
X
X\section{Emulate Knob Twist}
X
X{\em \center
Xknob id value
X}
X
XThis command is used to emulate a "knob twist".
XGenerally this command is used for display devices which have no actual
Xknob peripherals (eg. tek).
XAny non-zero number entered for "value" is converted to 1 (if "value" is
Xgreater than zero) or is converted to -1 (if "value is less than zero).
XThe user must enter the same command with "value" equal to zero to
Xstop the action envoked by the knob twist.
X
XThe "id" defines which knob is to be "twisted":
X
X\begin{tabular}{rl}
X	x	& rotates about x-axis \\
X	y	& rotates about y-axis \\
X	z	& rotates about z-axis \\
X	X	& slew view in x direction \\
X	Y	& slew view in y direction \\
X	Z	& zoom the view \\
X\end{tabular}
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X       knob x 1 \\
X       knob x 0 \\
X       knob Z -1 \\
X       knob Z 0 \\
X}
X
X\section{Solid\_Edit Named Solid}
X
X{\em\center
Xsed name
X}
X
XThis command allows one to immediately enter the solid edit mode
Xwith the solid "name" as the edited solid.
XNote that the solid must be displayed but not multiply referenced.
X
X\section{Illuminate Named Object}
X
X{\em\center
Xill name
X}
X
XThis command is used to illuminate an object ... a path containing this
Xobject ("name") will be illuminated.
XThis command is primarily used with display devices which do not have
Xa tablet to pick objects for editing.
X
X\section{Rotate the View}
X
X{\em\center
Xvrot xdeg ydeg zdeg
X}
X
XThis command rotates the VIEW "xdeg" degrees about the screen x-axis,
X"ydeg" degrees about the screen y-axis, and "zdeg" degrees about the
Xscreen z-axis.
X
XThis command is useful when the precise rotation desired is known.
XIt is also useful when in a rotation edit mode, and the viewing
Xrotation needs to be changed, without affecting the current edit.
X
X\section{Move Screen Center}
X
X{\em\center
Xcenter xx.xx yy.yy zz.zz
X}
X
XThis command moves the screen center to (xx.xx, yy.yy, zz.zz).
XUsing this command is one way of slewing the view.
X
X\section{Set View Size}
X
X{\em\center
Xsize xx.xx
X}
X
XThis command sets the view size to xx.xx and is one way of zooming
Xthe display.
XMaking the view size smaller has the effect of zooming in on the view.
X
X\section{Extended List of all Objects in Displaylist}
X
X{\em\center
Xx
X}
X
XThis command produces a list of all objects displayed, listing the center
Xof the object, its size, and if it is in the present view.
XIt is intended primarily for software debugging.
X
X\section{Refresh Display}
X
X{\em\center
Xrefresh
X}
X
XThis command will send a new display list to the display device.
X
X\section{Print View Status}
X
X{\em\center
Xstatus
X}
X
XThis is a debug command which prints the status of the current view,
Xincluding all viewing and editing matrices.
X
X\section{Simulate Button Press}
X
X{\em\center
Xpress button-label
X}
X
XThis command allows one to emulate a button press and is generally used
Xon display devices which do not have actual button peripherals.
XThe following are the strings allowed for "button-label" and all produce
Xthe indicated view on the device screen:
X        top, bottom, right, left, front, rear, 90,90, 35,25
X
XThe following is a listing of the remaining acceptable strings for
X"button-label" and the resulting action:
X
X\begin{tabular}{rl}
X       reset         &  reset the view \\
X       save          &  save the present view \\
X       restore       &  restor the saved view \\
X       adc           & display the angle-distance cursor \\
X       oill          &  begin object illumination (pick) \\
X       sill          & begin solid illumination (pick) \\
X       oscale        & object scale \\
X       ox            & object translat ion in x direction only \\
X       oy            & object translation in y direction only \\
X       oxy           & object translation \\
X       orot          & object rotation \\
X       sedit         & put up solid parameter menu \\
X       srot          & solid rotation \\
X       sxy           & solid translation \\
X       sscale        & solid scale \\
X       accept        & accept editing done \\
X       reject        & reject editing done \\
X\end{tabular}
X
XExamples:
X{\em
X         press 90,90 \\
X         press front \\
X         press oill \\
X         press orot \\
X         press reject \\
X}
X
X\section{Escape to the Shell}
X
X{\em\center
X%
X}
X
XThis command allows one to escape to the shell to perform multiple commands
Xwithout having to terminate the current MGED session.
XTo return to mged, enter a control-d to the Shell.
XNote that the "!" escape at the beginning of a line can be used
Xto send a single command to the shell.
X
X\section{Get Short Help Listing}
X
X{\em\center
X?
X}
X
XThis is the short form of the help command,
Xthat lists the names of all MGED commands.
X
X\section{Get Long Help Listing}
X
X{\em\center
Xhelp
X}
X
XThis is the long form of the help command,
Xthat produces a listing of all the available commands and their
Xarguments, and a one sentence summary of the commands purpose.
X
X\section{Exit (Quit) MGED}
X
X{\em\center
Xq
X}
X
XRunning the "q" command, or entering an End-Of-File (EOF) (typ. Control/D)
Xis the normal way of exiting MGED.
X
X\section{Copy and Translate TGC}
X
X{\em \center
Xcpi oldtgc newtgc
X}
X
XThis command is a specialized copy command and is designed to be used when one
Xis "running wires" in a description.
XThe object being copied must a cylindrical solid (TGC).
XThe following occurs when cpi is used:  first the cylinder ("oldtgc") is
Xcopied to "newtgc"; then "newtgc" is translated to the end of "oldtgc";
Xthen "newtgc" is displayed; and finally, MGED is put in the SOLID EDIT state
Xwith "newtgc" as the edited solid.
X
X\section{Remove Object and All References}
X
X{\em \center
Xkillall obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will accomplish two things:  first, the object[s] will be
Xremoved from the data file just as in the "kill" command;  second, all
Xreferences to the object[s] will also be removed.
X
X\section{Remove Complete Tree}
X
X{\em \center
Xkilltree obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will remove from the file complete trees originating with
Xobj1, obj2, ..., objn.
XEvery object in the designated paths will be removed from the file, hence
XCAUTION is urged.
XMake sure that "killtree" is what you want to do.
XUsing the "paths" or "tree" command on an object before "killtree" will
Xshow what objects will be killed.
X
X\section{Add Color To Display}
X
X{\em \center
Xcolor low high r g b string
X}
X
XThis command allows one to make color assignments to a range of item codes.
XThe arguments "low" and "high" are the item ranges.
XThe arguments "r", "g", and "b" are the red, green, and blue values
Xrespectively (the range of these numbers is generally 0-255).
XThe argument "string" is a string describing this class of items.
XA blank is considered a terminator, so there can be no blanks in
Xthis string.
X
X\section{Edit Display Colors}
X
X{\em \center
Xedcolor
X}
X
XThis command allows one to edit the existing color assignments (table).
XThe changes are made using the user's "selected" text editor
Xfound in environment variable EDITOR.
XNote that this method of specifying object colors is obsolete,
Xand has been replaced by the {\em mater} command.
X
X\section{Print Display Colors}
X
X{\em \center
Xprcolor
X}
X
XThis command prints the color assignments as they presently exist.
X
X\section{Find Objects}
X
X{\em \center
Xfind obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will find ALL references of obj1 obj2 ... objn in the file.
X
X\section{Estimate Presented Area}
X
X{\em \center
Xarea [tolerance]
X}
X
XThis command finds an estimate of the presented area of all E'd objects
Xin the present view from that aspect.
XThe argument "tolerance" is the tolerance for the endpoints of
Xline segments being "equal" and is optional.
X
X\section{Produce UNIX Plot}
X
X{\em \center
Xplot [-zclip] [-2d] [out-file] [| filter]
X}
X
XThis command is used to produce a UNIX-plot hardcopy of the present view of
Xthe 'geometry' on the display device.
XThe MGED faceplate will not be drawn.
XSome useful examples are:
X
X\begin{tabular}{rl}
Xplot-fb & LIBFB framebuffer (low res) \\
Xplot-fb -h & LIBFB framebuffer (high res) \\
Xtplot -Ti10 & Imagen laser printer \\
Xtplot -Tmeg & Megatek 7250 \\
Xtplot -T4014 & Tek4014 \\
Xtplot -Thpgl & HP7550A plotter
X\end{tabular}
X
X\section{Text Edit Solid Parameters}
X
X{\em \center
Xted
X}
X
XThis command allows one to edit a solid's parameters using the text editor
Xdefined by the users's path.
XThe solid being edited (solid edit mode) will be the one that will be
X"text edited".
X
X\section{Keyboard Input of Solid Parameters}
X
X{\em \center
Xin name type {parameters}
X}
X
XThis command allows one to enter a new solid directly via the keyboard.
XThe user will be prompted for any missing input and the solid will be
Xdisplayed on the screen.  WARNING: only minimal checking of parameters
Xis done.
X
X\section{Change View Azimuth, Elevation}
X
X{\em \center
Xae az elev
X}
X
XThis command sets the display viewing angles using the input azimuth (az)
Xand elevation (elev) angles.
X
X\section{Define Region Identifiers}
X
X{\em \center
Xregdef item [air los mat]
X}
X
XThis command allows one to change the default codes which will be given
Xto the next region created.
XIf the "air" code is non-zero, then the "item" code will be set to zero.
X
X\section{Change Edge Direction}
X
X{\em \center
Xedgedir delta\_x delta\_y delta\_z
X}
X
XThis command allows one to define the direction of an ARB edge being moved.
XIf only two arguments are input, the code assumes these to be the
Xrotation and fallback angles for the edge.
XIf three arguments are present, the code will use them as "deltas" to
Xdefine the direction of the edge.
XNote that this command can be useful to find the intersection of
Xa line (edge) with planes (faces).
X
X\section{Prefix Object Names}
X
X{\em \center
Xprefix string obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will prefix obj1, obj2, .... objn with "string".  All occurences
Xof these names will be prefixed.  String matching is allowed for the objects
Xto prefix.
X
X\section{Keep Objects in Another File}
X
X{\em \center
Xkeep file.g obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command allows one to keep the listed objects in the file "file.g".
XThis command is useful for pulling out parts of a description.
X
X\section{List Object Hierarchy}
X
X{\em \center
Xtree obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will print the tree structure for the objects listed.
X
X\section{Create Inside Solid}
X
X{\em \center
Xinside
X}
X
XThis command is used to define a solid (inside solid) such that when it is subtracted
Xfrom another certain solid (outside solid), the resulting region will have desired
Xthicknesses.
XTo invoke this option, enter "inside".
XYou will then be prompted for the required data.
XIf you are in the solid edit mode, the "outside solid" will default to the
Xsolid presently being edited.
XIf you are in the object edit mode, the "outside solid" will default to the
X"key solid" of the object path being edited.
XIf you are not in an edit mode, you will then be asked for the name of
Xthe "outside solid".
XNext, you will be asked what name you wish to call the new "inside solid"
Xto be calculated.
XFinally, you will be asked to enter the thickness[es], depending on the
Xsolid type.
XThe "inside solid" will then be displayed on the screen.
XIf the thickness values input are negative, then the thickness will be
Xdirected to the "outside" of the solid.
X
X\section{Produce ASCII Summary of Solids}
X
X{\em \center
Xsolids file obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will produce an ascii summary of all solids involved with
Xobjects obj1, obj2, ..., objn.  This summary will be written in 'file'.
XIn this file, all regions and solids are numbered and will match the
Xnumbers of a COMGEOM deck produced by VDECK or GIFT if the objects are
Xentered in the same order.
XThe file 'file' will be overwritten if it already exists.
XString matching is allowed for the objects.
X
X\section{Produce ASCII Summary of Regions}
X
X{\em \center
Xregions file obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will produce an ascii summary table of all regions involved with
Xobjects obj1, obj2,...,objn.
XThis summary table will be written in 'file'.
XIn this file, all regions and solids will be numbered and will match the numbers
Xof a COMGEOM description produced by VDECK or GIFT if the objects are entered
Xin the same order.
XThis file will be identical to the "solids" command except the actual
Xparameters are not listed.
XThe file 'file' will be overwritten if it already exists.
XString matching is allowed for the object names.
X
X\section{Produce ASCII Summary of Idents}
X
X{\em \center
Xidents file obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will produce an ascii summary table of all region idents involved with
Xobjects obj1, obj2,...,objn.
XThis summary table will be written in 'file'.
XIn this file, all regions will be numbered and will match the region numbers
Xof a COMGEOM description produced by VDECK or GIFT if the objects are entered
Xin the same order.
XAt the end of this file will be the same region information, but ordered
Xby ident number.
XThe file 'file' will be overwritten if it already exists.
XString matching is allowed for the object names.
X
X\section{List Objects Paths}
X
X{\em \center
Xpaths
X}
X
XThis command will print ALL paths matching an "input" path.
XYou will be asked to enter the path to match.
XThe path members are entered on ONE line, seperated by spaces.
XThe input path need not be a complete path, but must contain at least one object.
XAll paths with the same first members as the input path will be listed.
XThis command is useful for finding complete paths which begin with certain objects.
X
X\section{List Evaluated Path Solid}
X
X{\em \center
Xlisteval
X}
X
XThis command will "evaluate" and list ALL paths matching an input path, including the
Xparameters of the solids at the bottom of each path.
XThese parameters will reflect any editing contained in the path listed.
XYou will be asked to enter the path to match.
XThe path members are entered on ONE line, seperated by spaces.
XThe input path need not be a complete path, but must contain at least
Xone object.
XNote that since the solid parameters are printed, this could be a
Xrather lengthy listing depending on the completeness of the input path.
X
X\section{Evaluate Path and Copy Solid}
X
X{\em \center
Xcopyeval
X}
X
XThis command allows one to copy an "evaluated solid", that is a complete path
Xending in a solid.
XYou will be asked to enter a complete path.
XAgain, this path is entered on ONE line with the members seperated by spaces.
XIf you do not know the complete path, use the "paths" command above to find it.
XNext, you will be asked to enter the name of this copied solid.
XThe input path will be traversed and the accumulated path transformations will
Xbe applied to the parameters of the bottom solid.
XThese new parameters will then be the copied solid.
XNote:  this command is useful for making "dummy solids" to subtract for
Xoverlaps between objects which have been "object" edited.
X
X\section{Edit Objects Region Identifiers}
X
X{\em \center
Xedcodes obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command provides for an easy way to modify the code numbers (item, air, material, and los)
Xof ALL regions found in paths beginning with an object.
XFor each object, all paths beginning with that object are traversed until a region
Xis encountered...at which time the following is listed:
X
Xitem  air  mat  los      /obj1/.../region.n
X
XThe cursor then jumps back to "item" at the beginning of the line.
XAt this time the cursor can be advanced only by entering a new item code
X(only digits are allowed) or by hitting the "space bar" or "tab key".
XThe space and tab will move the cursor to the next position in the line.
XPressing the "backspace key" will move the cursor to the beginning of
Xthe next location to the left.
XMoving the cursor "past" the los location
Xwill return it to the beginning of the line.
XWhen the code numbers are as you desire,
Xa RETURN will print the next line
Xfor editing.
XAt any time, pressing the "R" key will restore the idents on the current
Xline to the way they were originally.
XA Control/C or a "q" will abort the process at the current line.
XString matching is allowed for the object names.
X
X\section{List Object As Stored}
X
X{\em \center
Xtab obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will produce a listing of objects as they are stored in
Xthe MGED object data file.
XString matching is allowed for the objects.
X
X\section{List Regions With Given Ident}
X
X{\em \center
Xwhichid item1 item2 ... itemn
X}
X
XThis command will list ALL regions in the data file which have certain
Xitem codes.
X
X\section{Create ARB Given 3 Points}
X
X{\em \center
X3ptarb
X}
X
XThis command will produce a "plate mode" arb8 given 3 points on one face, 2 coordinates
Xof the 4th point on that face, and a thickness.
XThe 3rd coordinate of the 4th point will be solved for and the "other" face
Xwill be a normal distance (== the desired thickness) away.
XYou will be asked for all necessary input.
X
X\section{Create ARB Given Point and Angles}
X
X{\em \center
Xrfarb
X}
X
XThis command will produce a "plate mode" arb8 given a point on one face,
Xrotation and fallback angles for that face, 2 coordinates of the 3
Xremaining points on that face, and a thickness.
XThe 3rd coordinates of the three points will be solved for, and the other
Xface will be a normal distance equal to "thickness" away.
XYou will be asked for all necessary input.
X
X\section{Push Editing Down Paths}
X
X{\em \center
Xpush obj1 obj2 ... objn
X}
X
XThis command will "push" an object's path transformations to the solid's parameters
Xlocated at the bottom of each path.
XIf a conflict is encountered, then an error message is printed and NOTHING is done.
XA conflict occurs when the same solid "ends" different paths but the transformations
Xare different.
XConflicts could occur when "instanced" or "copied" groups occur in an object's
Xpaths or when a solid is a member of 2 regions which have been edited separately.
XA complication of this command, which will not be listed as a conflict, is when a solid's parameters have been
Xchanged by a push, yet this solid is referenced by another object which was NOT
Xincluded in the push.
XThe user should beware of this situation.
XThis command can be very useful when "adding" parts from another file.
XOnce the "object editing" of these new parts is completed, the push command
Xwill put the editing done to the solid level.
XSince the added parts should have no cross-references with the existing
Xobjects, there should be no problems.
X
X\section{Check For Duplicate Names}
X
X{\em \center
Xdup file.g {string}
X}
X
XThis command will compare the current object data file with another
XMGED file "file.g" and list any object names common to both files.
XIf "string" is present, all object names in "file.g" will be prefixed with
X"string" before comparing for duplicate names.
XGenerally, one uses "string" only when duplicate names are found without it.
X
X\section{Concat Files}
X
X{\em \center
Xconcat file.g {string}
X}
X
XThis command will concatenate another MGED file "file.g" onto the present
Xobject data file.
XIf "string" is present, all names in "file.g" will be prefixed with this
Xstring.
XNo objects from "file.g" will be added if the name already occurs in the
Xcurrent object file...the object names will be listed and skipped.
XHowever, this command should be used in conjunction with the "dup" command to
Xeliminate any problems with duplicate names.
X
X\section{Create Pseudo-Track}
X
X{\em \center
Xtrack
X}
X
XThis command adds track components to the data file to fit specified
X"wheel" data.
XSolids, regions, and a group containing the regions will be created and
Xdisplayed on the screen.
XYou will be prompted for all required data.
X
X\section{Define ARB Face}
X
X{\em \center
Xfacedef \#\#\#\#
X}
X
XThis command is used to define the face plane of an ARB that is being edited.
XThe following is the option menu displayed when this command is used:
X        a     planar equation
X        b     3 points
X        c     rot and fb angles + fixed point
X        d     same plane thru fixed point
X        q     quit
XTo select any of these methods of defining a plane, enter the appropriate
Xletter.  You will then be asked for the desired input.
X
X\section{Define Plane Equation of ARB Face}
X
X{\em \center
Xeqn [A B C]
X}
X
XThis command is used when one is rotating the face of an edited ARB and defines
Xthe coefficients of the face planar equation (Ax + By + Cz).
X
X\section{Move (Rename) Everywhere}
X
X{\em \center
Xmvall old new
X}
X
XThis command is used to rename all occurrences of an object in the data file.  In this
Xcase, the object "old" will be renamed "new" for every occurence.
X
X\section{Miscellaneous Commands}
X
XIt is possible to view, specify, and text-edit
Xinformation pertaining to the material type and color of various
Xparts of the model tree.  This is an interim capability
Xintended to provide enough material properties information for
Xcurrent rendering and analysis purposes until the design of a
Xfull material properties database can be finalized.
X
XIn addition to a variety of usual database manipulation
Xand status commands, there are commands to
Xcompare the current database for name overlap (conflicts)
Xwith another database, as well as commands to import and export
Xsubtrees to/from the current database.
XIf name conflicts between the two databases
Xdo exist, there are commands to rename an individual node without
Xchanging any of the references to it (``mv''), or to rename
Xa node and change all the references to it (``mvall'').
XAnother command which is useful for preparing to move subtrees between
Xdatabases is the ``push'' command,
Xwhich adjusts the transformation matrices from the indicated point
Xdown to the leaves of the directed acyclic graph, leaving the higher
Xlevel arcs with identity matrices.
X
X\section{UNIX-Plot Output}
X
XThe ``plot'' command can store an exact image of the current
X(non-faceplate) display on the screen, either using the
XSystem V standard 2-D monochrome UNIX-Plot ({\em plot(4)}) format,
Xor the BRL 3-D color extended-UNIX-Plot format.
XThese plots can be sent to a disk file,
Xor ``piped'' directly to a filter process.
XThis can be useful for making hard copies of the current MGED view
Xfor showing to others,
Xusing a local pen plotter or laser printer.
X
X\section{Ray-Tracing the Current View}
X
XAn important capability even beyond the ability to generate an
Xevaluated boundary wireframe is the ability of MGED to initiate a
Xquick ray-trace rendering of the current view on any nearby framebuffer!
XThis is implemented by using the MGED ``rt'' command to fork off
Xan instance of the RT program, and sending the RT program
Xa description of the current view
Xwith any user-specified options.
XThis allows the designer to
Xuse the power of MGED to select the desired view, and then to
Xquickly verify the geometry and light source placement.
XA 50 by 50 pixel rendering of the current view can usually be done
Xin less than a minute (on a DEC VAX-780 class processor), and allows
Xfor general verification before the designer uses the ``saveview''
Xcommand to submit a batch job for a high resolution ray-trace of
Xthe same view.
X
X\section{Animation}
X
XThe MGED editor includes a number of features which are useful
Xfor developing animation tools and scripts.
XThe full description of the current viewing transformation and eye position
Xcan be saved in a file,
Xand such a previously saved view can be read back at any time,
Ximmediately changing the editor's view.
XIn addition, the current viewing transformation and eye position can be
Xappended to a file containing a collection of keyframes.
XMost importantly, a file full of keyframe information, either raw keyframe
Xpositions or smoothly interpolated keyframe sequences, can
Xby ``played'' in real time using MGED,
Xproviding a powerful and fast animation preview capability.
X
XAs a separate animation capability intended
Xfor developing demonstrations and instructional material relating to the
Xuse of the MGED editor,
Xall user interactions with the editor can be recorded in a file,
Xalong with an indication of the time elapsed between user actions.
XThis file can be  adjusted using a normal text editor to remove any errors,
Xor to eliminate dead time where the user stopped to think.
XOnce created, this session script can be replayed through the editor
Xat any time, either to provide a smooth ``canned'' demonstration
Xbefore a live audience, or to create a film or videotape.
END-of-e.tex
