X\chapter{TUTORIALS ON EDITING SOLIDS}
X
XThe Solid Editing state of MGED is used to modify the fundamental
Xparameters of an individual solid.
XEach solid must be modified individually.
X
X\section{Solid Edit: A Six-Sided Polyhedron}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-top.ps}
X\caption{Top View of ARB8.}
X\label{es8-top}
X\end{figure}
X
XThis section illustrates the use of commands while in
XSOL EDIT state to alter the
Xshape of a polyhedron with six sides and 8 faces (ARB8).
X
X\noindent{\tt
X\$ {\em mged es.g} \\
XBRL-CAD Release 3.0 Graphics Editor (MGED) Compilation 82 \\
X    Thu Sep 22 08:08:39 EDT 1988 \\
X    mike@video.brl:/cad/.mged.4d2 \\
X \\
Xes.g: No such file or directory \\
XCreate new database (y|n)[n]? {\em y} \\
Xattach (nu|tek|tek4109|ps|plot|sgi)[nu]? {\em sgi} \\
XATTACHING sgi (SGI 4d) \\
XUntitled MGED Database (units=mm) \\
Xmged> {\em in arb8 rpp -1 1 -1 1 -1 1} \\
Xmged> {\em size 10} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{es8-top}
Xis a top view of the six-sided polyhedron.
XThe Z-axis perpendicular to the viewing screen.
XNext, the view is rotated so that all sides can be seen.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Twist ROTY knob clockwise and restore} \\
Xmged> {\em Twist ROTX knob counter-clockwise and restore} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-rot.ps}
X\caption{A Rotated View of the ARB8.}
X\label{es8-rot}
X\end{figure}
XFigure \ref{es8-rot} shows a better perspective of the solid.
X
XThe next step in this tutorial is to transfer to the solid edit state.
XThis can be accomplished in two ways:  either by going through
Xthe SOL PICK state (``illuminate mode'') or by direct transfer via
Xkeyboard command.
XUsing illuminate mode is better when the name of the solid to be
Xedited may not be known, while the keyboard command is generally
Xpreferred when the name of the solid is known.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Solid Illum'' entry in the button menu} \\
Xmged> {\em Move the mouse out of the menu area} \\
Xmged> {\em Click the mouse to enter SOL EDIT state} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XTo perform a direct transfer from the viewing state to the solid edit state
Xusing a keyboard command, enter:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em sed arb8} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-sed.ps}
X\caption{An ARB8 in Solid Edit State.}
X\label{es8-sed}
X\end{figure}
X
XFigure \ref{es8-sed} corresponds to the view on the display.
XThe ARB8 MENU is unique to the ARB primitive,
Xand lists operations that can only be performed on an ARB solid.
XThe items in the ARB8 MENU are
Xselected by using the mouse.
XEach of the other types of solids have a
Xsimilar unique menu.
XWhen one of these items is selected, the top level ARB8 MENU disappears,
Xto be replaced with the indicated subordinate menu.
XThe top-level menu reappears when either
Xthe ``edit menu'' item in the SOLID EDIT menu is selected,
Xor the ``RETURN'' item in the subordinate menu is selected.
X
XThe  SOLID EDIT  menu applies to all
Xsolids when in the SOL EDIT state.
XThe items in the  SOLID EDIT  menu are selected
Xby either using the mouse or by depressing the appropriate button on the
Xbutton box.
XWhen any of the SOLID EDIT menu items are selected
X(eg, ``Rotate'', ``Translate'', ``Scale''), the solid-specific menu
Xdisappears.
XTh top-level solid-specific menu reappears when
Xthe ``edit menu'' item in the SOLID EDIT menu is selected.
X
XThe {\em p [params]} command is used to
Xmake precise changes, where the numeric value of the parameter being
Xedited is know.
XValues for all parameters in the ARB8
Xand SOLID EDIT menus can be specified by using the {\em p} command,
Xor by pointing and clicking with the mouse.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-tr0.ps}
X\caption{Translating ARB8 Point 1 to the Origin.}
X\label{es8-tr0}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{Translate Operation}
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Translate'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0 0 0} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XPoint 1 of the primitive is moved to point 0 0 0,
Xas shown in Figure \ref{es8-tr0}.
X
XThe translate solid operation is selected
Xby either picking ``Translate'' on the solid edit menu
Xwith the mouse, by depressing the solid edit button on the button box,
Xor by entering the {\em press sed} command.
XParameters to the translate solid operation
Xare of the form {\em p a b c}
Xwhere {\em a}, {\em b}, and {\em c} are the new coordinates
Xof point 1 in the solid.
XThe other points are transferred to keep the same position
Xrelative to point 1.
XThe general form of the new coordinates for point is
X
X\begin{center}
X\begin{verbatim}
Xx ' = x + a - x
Xy ' = y + b - y
XZ ' = Z + c - Z
X\end{verbatim}
X\end{center}
X
XThe command
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 1 -1 -1} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
Xcan be used to restore the primitive to the original position.
X
X\subsection{Rotate Operation}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-xrot.ps}
X\caption{Solid Edit Rotation of 45 Degrees about X.}
X\label{es8-xrot}
X\end{figure}
X
XThe rotate operation is initiated by either selecting Rotate on the menu
Xscreen with the mouse,
Xby depressing the Solid Rotate button on the button box,
Xor by entering the {\em press srot} command on the keyboard.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Rotate'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 45 0 0} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThe parameter {\em p} command is used to make precise rotation changes.
XThe
Xcommand is entered in the form {\em p a b c} where
X{\em a}, {\em b}, and {\em c} are the angles
X(in degrees) of rotation about the x, y, and z axes respectively.  Point 1,
Xthe vertex, remains fixed, and the solid is rotated about this point.  A
Xpositive angle of rotation is counter-clockwise when viewed in the positive
Xdirection along an axis.
X
XThe order of rotation is not commutative.
XRotation takes place about the
XZ axis, Y axis, and X axis in that order.
XFigure \ref{es8-xrot} shows the rotation of 45 degrees about the X axis.
X
X%The following is the formula for moving point (x,y,z) through angles
X%(a, b, c) to point (x', y', z')
X%\begin{verbatim}
X%[X'] [cos b cos c                     -cos b sin c        sin b        ][X]
X%[Y']=[sin a sin b cos c +cos a sin b   cos a cos c -sin a sin b sin c -sin a cos b ][Y]
X%[Z'] [sin a sin c -cos a sin b cos c   cos a sin b sin c + sin a cos c cos a cos b ][Z]
X%\end{verbatim}
X
XThe values entered after the p are absolute - the rotations are applied to
Xthe primitive as it existed when solid rotation was first selected.  Thus
Xentering {\em p 0 0 0} will undo any rotations
Xperformed since solid rotation was begun.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-yrot.ps}
X\caption{Solid Edit Rotation of 45 Degrees about Y.}
X\label{es8-yrot}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-zrot.ps}
X\caption{Solid Edit Rotation of 45 Degrees about Z.}
X\label{es8-zrot}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 0 45 0} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{es8-yrot} displays the solid
Xafter it has been rotated about the Y axis.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 0 0 45} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{es8-zrot} displays the solid
Xafter it has been rotated about the Z axis.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 0 0 0} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThis restores the original orientation of the solid.
X
X\subsection{Scale Operation}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-scale.ps}
X\caption{ARB8 Scale Increased by 2X.}
X\label{es8-scale}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Scale'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 2} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{es8-scale} corresponds to the view that is shown on the display.
XThe scale operation may be initiated by either selecting
Xthe Scale entry  on the menu with the mouse,
Xby depressing the Solid Scale button,
Xor by entering {\em press sscale} on the keyboard.
XThe parameter command {\em p n} is
Xused to enter a precise scale factors, where {\em n} is
Xthe scale factor.
XThe coordinates of point 1 remain the same.  The distances
Xfrom point 1 to the other points are multiplied by the scale value {\em n}.
XThe general equations for the transformation from point p to p' are
X
X\begin{verbatim}
X    x'[i] = x[i] + n (x[i] - x[1] )
X    y'[i] = y[i] + n (y[i] - y[1] )   i != 1
X    z'[i] = z[i] + n (z[i] - z[1] )
X\end{verbatim}
X
XThe size of the primitive may be changed by depressing the mouse at
Xdifferent positions.  When the mouse is clicked, the
Xedited primitive is scaled about point 1 (the key point)
Xby an amount proportional
Xto the distance the mouse is from the center of the screen.  If the mouse
Xis above the center of the screen, the edited primitive will become larger.
XIf the
Xmouse is below the center, the primitive will become smaller.
X
XThe value of {\em n} entered is applied to the primitive as it existed when the
Xsolid scale state was entered.
X
XEntering {\em p 1} will return the primitive
Xto the size it had when the solid scale operation first started.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 1} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-edge1.ps}
X\caption{ARB8 Edge 15 Moved Through (9, -2, -2).}
X\label{es8-edge1}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-edge2.ps}
X\caption{ARB8 Edge 12 Moved Through (2, 5, -2).}
X\label{es8-edge2}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-edge3.ps}
X\caption{ARB8 Edge 14 Moved Through (2, -2, 7).}
X\label{es8-edge3}
X\end{figure}
X
X\subsection{Moving Edges}
X
XThe move edge command permits the moving of a line or edge so that the
Xline passes through the selected point.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``edit menu'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em Select the ``move edges'' entry in the ARB menu} \\
Xmged> {\em Select the ``move edge 15'' entry in the ARB8 edges menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 9 -2 -2} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThe edge 15 is moved so that it passes through the point (9, -2, -2).  The
Xcoordinates of the new points 1 and 5 are the intersection of the new edge
Xwith the planes 234 and 678.  Since both the old edge and new edge 15 are
Xparallel to the X axis,
Xthe X coordinate of the point given by the {\em p} command
Xhas no meaning.  The X coordinates for points 1 and 5 are not changed.
XSee Figure \ref{es8-edge1}.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 9 -1 -1} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThis restores the original shape.
XThe choice of ``9'' for the X coordinate was arbitrary.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``move edge 12'' entry in the ARB8 edges menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 2 5 -2} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThe edge 12 is parallel to the Y axis.  This command moves the points 1
Xand 2 so that their X and Z coordinates are 2 and -2.
XSee Figure \ref{es8-edge2}.
XThe Y coordinates are not changed.
X
XTo restore the view, enter:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 1 5 -1} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThe choice of ``5'' for the Y coordinate was arbitrary.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``move edge 14'' entry in the ARB8 edges menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 2 -2 7} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThe edge 14 is parallel to the Z axis.
XThis command moves the points 1
Xand 4 so that their X and Y coordinates are 2 and -2.
XSee Figure \ref{es8-edge3}.
XThe Z coordinates are not changed.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 1 -1 7} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThis restores the original shape.
XThe choice of ``7'' for the Z coordinate was arbitrary.
X
X\subsection{Extrude Command}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-ex1.ps}
X\caption{ARB8 Rear Face Extruded 5 Units in -Z.}
X\label{es8-ex1}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es8-ex2.ps}
X\caption{ARB8 Rear Face Extruded 3 Units in +Z.}
X\label{es8-ex2}
X\end{figure}
X
XThe extrude command is used to move the opposite surface a distance from
Xthe specified surface or plate.
XThis command can only be used when an ARB solid is in
Xsolid edit state.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em extrude 1265 5} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XIn Figure \ref{es8-ex1},
Xthe plane opposite surface whose points are 1, 2, 6, and 5
Xis moved to a distance of 5 in the positive Z direction from plane 1265.  Note
Xthat the points were selected counter-clockwise when viewed in the positive
Xdirection along the Z axis.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em extrude 1562 3} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XIn Figure \ref{es8-ex2},
Xthe plane opposite surface 1562 is moved to a distance of 3
Xin the negative Z direction from 1562.  Note that the points were selected
Xclockwise when viewed in the positive direction along the Z axis.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em extrude 1265 2} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThis restores the original shape of this solid.
X
XTo return control to the VIEWING state, select the ``REJECT Edit''
Xitem on the button menu, press the ``reject'' button on the button box,
Xor enter the command {\em press reject} on the keyboard.
XThen, enter
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em d arb8} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
Xto drop the ARB8 from view.
X
X\section{Solid Edit:  A Five-Sided Polyhedron}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es5-top.ps}
X\caption{Top View of an ARB5.}
X\label{es5-top}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es5-rot.ps}
X\caption{A Rotated View of the ARB5.}
X\label{es5-rot}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es5-sed.ps}
X\caption{The ARB5 in Solid Edit State.}
X\label{es5-sed}
X\end{figure}
X
XThis tutorial illustrates the application of the SOL EDIT state to the ARB5
Xsolid.
XIn this tutorial, the view is modified by using the rotation
Xknobs so that all sides can be seen.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em size 6} \\
Xmged> {\em in arb5 arb5} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z for point 1: {\em 0 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z for point 2: {\em 0 0 1} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z for point 3: {\em 0 1 1} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z for point 4: {\em 0 1 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z for point 5: {\em -1 .5 .5} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{es5-top} is the display of arb5
Xin the VIEWING state that is seen when
Xthe solid is first created.
XIn this view, the Z axis is perpendicular to the viewing screen.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Twist ROTY knob clockwise and restore} \\
Xmged> {\em Twist ROTX knob counter-clockwise and restore} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThese actions generate a view shown in Figure \ref{es5-rot}
Xthat shows all sides.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Solid Illum'' entry in the button menu} \\
Xmged> {\em Move the mouse out of the menu area} \\
Xmged> {\em Click the mouse to enter SOL EDIT state} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThese actions will place MGED in the SOL EDIT state
Xas shown in Figure \ref{es5-sed}.
X
X\subsection{Translate Operation}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es5-tr.ps}
X\caption{Translating an ARB5.}
X\label{es5-tr}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Translate'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p -1 -1 1} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThis command cause point 1 to be moved to coordinates (-1, -1, 1) and the
Xother points are moved so that they keep the same relative position to point
X1.  See Figure \ref{es5-tr}.
X
XEnter this command to restore the solid to it's original location:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em p 0 0 0} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\subsection{Rotate Operation}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{es5-xrot.ps}
X\caption{ARB5 Solid Edit Rotation about X.}
X\label{es5-xrot}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Rotate'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 45 0 0} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{es5-xrot} shows a rotation of 45 degrees
Xabout an axis parallel to the X axis.
XThe rotate command is entered in the form {\em p a b c}
