X\section{Solid Edit: Alter a Cylinder}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{esc-top.ps}
X\caption{Top View of a Cylinder.}
X\label{esc-top}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{esc-rot.ps}
X\caption{A Rotated View of the Cylinder.}
X\label{esc-rot}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{esc-sed.ps}
X\caption{A Cylinder in Solid Edit State.}
X\label{esc-sed}
X\end{figure}
X
XThis tutorial illustrates the application of the SOL EDIT state to
Xcylinder solids.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em size 12} \\
Xmged> {\em in cyl rcc} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vertex: {\em 0 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of height (H) vector: {\em 2 0 0} \\
XEnter radius: {\em 1}
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{esc-top} is the display of the cylinder solid
Xwhen viewed from the top.
XSince the
XZ axis is perpendicular to the viewing screen, a view of all sides cannot be
Xseen.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Twist ROTY knob clockwise and restore} \\
Xmged> {\em Twist ROTX knob counter-clockwise and restore} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThese actions generate a view, Figure \ref{esc-rot}, that shows all sides.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Solid Illum'' entry in the button menu} \\
Xmged> {\em Move the mouse out of the menu area} \\
Xmged> {\em Click the mouse to enter SOL EDIT state} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{esc-sed} is the view that displays the menu
Xfor the SOL EDIT state.
XThe
Xpoint V is at the origin (0,0,0) in this example and is in the middle of the
Xcircle that contains points A and B.  H is the point of the center of the
Xcircle that contains points C and D.  The coordinates of H are the coordinates
Xof the vector from V to H and represent the relative position of H to V.  Mag
Xis the magnitude of these vectors and is represented by the formula
X\begin{center}
X\begin{verbatim}
XMag = sqrt( x + y + z )
X\end{verbatim}
X\end{center}
X
X``H dir cos'' are the direction cosines of the vector H which
Xis perpendicular to plane of the points A, B, and V.  The coordinates of A
Xare the coordinates of the vector from V through A.  Mag is the magnitude of
Xthe vectors from V to A.  The coordinates of B are the coordinates of the
Xvectors from V through B.  Mag is the magnitude of the vector from V to B.
XThe values for c and d are the magnitudes of the vectors from the tip of
Xvector H to the points C
Xand D respectively.
X``A x B dir cos'' represents the direction cosines of the
Xvector ``A x B''.
X
