X\section{Object Editing a Six-Sided Polyhedron}
X
XThis tutorial illustrates the application of the {\bf OBJ EDIT} state to
Xthe ``arb8'' primitive.  The editing of the arb8 illustrates the
Xabsolute movement of the points.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{eo-start.ps}
X\caption{``arb8'' Object Edit; Top View.}
X\label{eo-start}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em e arb8}\\
Xvectorized in 0 seconds\\
Xmged> {\em size 8}\\
Xmged>\\
X{\em Select the {\bf BUTTON MENU} if not already displayed.} \\
X{\em Select the {\bf Object Illum} menu entry.} \\
X{\em Move the mouse away from the menu area and select twice.} \\
X}
X
XThese operations select an object for editing.
XControl is passed through the {\bf OBJ PICK} and {\bf OBJ PATH} states
Xto the {\bf OBJ EDIT} state.  The display should look similar to
XFigure \ref{eo-start}.
X
X\subsection{Scale Operation}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{eo-scale.ps}
X\caption{``arb8'' Object Edit; Scaled by 0.5.}
X\label{eo-scale}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em scale 0.5}\\
Xmged>\\
X}
X
XAs always, the selected operation operates with respect to the key
Xvertex -- point 1 remains the same, and the distances from point 1 to
Xthe other points are multiplied by the scale factor.  See Figure
X\ref{eo-scale}.  What will happen if another {\bf scale 0.5} command
Xis given?  The {\bf scale} operator is an absolute operator.  It sets
Xthe scale factor associated with a particular transformation matrix.
XIt does not multiply the current transformation matrix scale factor by
Xthe new scale factor.
X
X\subsection{X, Y, and XY Move Operation}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{eo-xyzmove.ps}
X\caption{``arb8'' Object Edit; Translated to (0.5, -2, 1.5).}
X\label{eo-xyzmove}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em scale 1}\\
Xmged> {\em translate .5 -2 1.5}\\
Xmged>\\
X{\em Select the {\bf X move} menu entry.}\\
X}
X
XThe first two commands undo the effects of the previous scale operation, and
Xtranslate the key point to (0.5, -2, 1.5).  The coordinates of the other
Xpoints are changed accordingly; preserving their distances relative
Xto point 1 (see Figure \ref{eo-xyzmove}).
XThe last operation above placed MGED into a state where the key point
Xof the object will track the X component of successive selects, but not the Y
Xcomponent. Note that on some displays point 1 may not be directly
Xvisible.  It is actually behind point 4. Watch the area listing the
Xinformation concerning ``arb8'' as selections are made.
X
X\noindent
X{\em Do several selects while moving the cursor slowly in a circle.}\\
X
X   Observe that only the X axis information changes. Similarly, the {\bf
XY move} tracks only changes in the Y axis, and {\bf XY move} tracks
Xchanges in both axes.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{eo-xymove.ps}
X\caption{XY Move.}
X\label{eo-xymove}
