X\section{Object Path and Object Edit}
X
XThis section illustrates the use of the {\bf OBJ PATH} state to select the
Xnumber of objects that are affected by one edit command.  In the previous
Xsections the user was shown how to manipulate only one primitive.  A group
Xof primitives may also be edited as a single entity.  This section
Xshows how an entire group may be edited without addressing each individual
Xprimitive.
X
XMGED generally has several ways to achieve a particular result.  In
Xthis section, keyboard commands are used instead of the control buttons and
Xthe display menu.  The creation and saving of special primitives is
Xillustrated.
X
XIn the database, the original primitives are centered around
Xthe origin.  Copies of these primitives will be made, translated away
Xfrom the origin and saved for future editing.
X
X\subsection{Organize the Primitives and Groups}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{eo-stacked.ps}
X\caption{Stacked Primatives.}
X\label{eo-stacked}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em cp arb8 arb8.s}\\
Xmged> {\em cp ellg ellg.s}\\
Xmged> {\em cp tgc tgc.s}\\
Xmged> {\em cp tor tor.s}\\
Xmged>\\
X}
X
XFigure \ref{eo-stacked} shows the four primitives; arb8.s, ellg.s, tgc.s,
Xand tor.s.  One convention frequently used by experienced modelers is to
Xtack an identifying suffix on the names of the various primitives and
Xobjects.  Often, a ``.s'' suffix denotes a {\em solid}, a ``.r'' denotes
Xa {\em region} and a ``.g'' denotes a {\em group} (note that this is a
Xdifferent ``.g'' from the ``.g'' suffix used with filenames.).
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em size 16}\\
Xmged> {\em sed arb8.s}\\
Xmged> {\em press sxy}\\
Xmged> {\em p 3 -3 1}\\
Xmged> {\em press accept}\\
Xmged>\\
X}
X
XSeveral things happened in the above sequence.  The net result is that
Xthe solid arb8.s was ``unstacked'' using a Solid Edit so it is more
Xvisible.  The same sequence of operations will be performed with the
Xother objects to move them to other locations.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{eo-spread.ps}
X\caption{Primatives After Translation.}
X\label{eo-spread}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em sed ellg.s}\\
Xmged> {\em press sxy}\\
Xmged> {\em p -3 3 1}\\
Xmged> {\em press accept}\\
Xmged> {\em sed tgc.s}\\
Xmged> {\em press sxy}\\
Xmged> {\em p -3 -3 1}\\
Xmged> {\em press accept}\\
Xmged> {\em sed tor.s}\\
Xmged> {\em press sxy}\\
Xmged> {\em p 3 3 1}\\
Xmged> {\em press accept}\\
Xmged>\\
X}
X
XThe screen should now look like Figure \ref{eo-spread}.  The next step
Xis to group the primitives
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em g a.g tgc.s arb8.s}\\
Xmged> {\em g b.g ellg.s tor.s}\\
Xmged> {\em g c.g a.g b.g}\\
Xmged> {\em B c.g}\\
Xvectorized in 0 sec\\
Xmged> {\em tree c.g}
X\begin{verbatim}
X| c.g_____________| a.g_____________| tgc.s
X                                    | arb8.s
X                  | b.g_____________| ellg.s
X                                    | tor.s
X\end{verbatim}
X\noindent
Xmged>\\
X}
X
XThe {\em group} operator ({\bf g}) generates an object, named by the
Xfirst argument, which is the union of all objects named in succeeding
Xarguments.  Therefore, the object ``a.g'' is composed of the union of
X``tgc.s'' and ``arb8.s''.  Likewise, the object ``c.g'' is the union of
X``a.g'' and ``b.g''.  The next command in the above sequence is called
Xthe {\em blast} command.  It is effectively a {\em zap} ({\bf Z})
Xfollowed by an {\em edit} ({\bf e}).
X
XThe final command is the {\em tree} command.  It is intended to give the
Xuser some idea of the hierarchical structure of an object.  It presents
Xa tree laid on it's side.  The root is at the left, and the leaves are
Xat the right. A vertical bar denotes a connection at a given level, with
Xthe proviso that a vertical bar having a line of underscores coming
Xin from the left represents the start of a particular subtree when read
Xfrom top down (``ellg.s'' and ``arb8.s'' do not have a common parent).
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{eo-grpath.ps}
X\caption{Object Path With ``tor.s'' as Reference Solid.}
X\label{eo-grpath}
X\end{figure}
X
X\noindent
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em press oill}\\
Xmged>\\
X{\em Move the cursor up and down the screen until the primitive ``tor.s''
Xis illuminated, then select}\\
X}
X
XSelecting the solid ``tor.s'' transitions MGED into the {\bf OBJ PATH}
Xstate, and establishes ``tor.s'' as the reference solid for any future
Xediting operations.
XNote that the name ``tor.s'' is shown in the upper left corner of the
Xdisplay, and on the second status line at the bottom of the display
X(Figure \ref{eo-grpath}).
X
XThe {\bf OBJ PATH} state has little meaning unless there is more than one path
Xor group in the display.  One of the following paths may be selected:
X
X\begin{quote}
Xc.g/b.g/\_MATRIX\_/tor.s
X
Xc.g/\_MATRIX\_/b.g/tor.s
X
X\_MATRIX\_/c.g/b.g/tor.s
X\end{quote}
X
XAlthough the torus primitive has been selected as the reference solid,
Xthe position of {\bf \_MATRIX\_} determines the extent of the effects of
Xthe edit.  The first choice affects only the torus.  The second choice
Xaffects everything under the group ``b.g'' (the torus and ellipsoid).
XThe third choice affects all of the primitives.  Remember though, that
Xin all cases, what is being edited is the Homogeneous Transformation
XMatrix (thought of as the arc connecting objects), not the underlying
Xsolid.
X
