X\chapter{BUILDING A TIN WOODSMAN}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-prims.ps}
X\caption{WoodsMan Primitives.}
X\label{wm-prims}
X\end{figure}
X
XThe purpose of this tutorial is to demonstrate how to build a model using
Xa few basic primitives.  The model to be constructed is a tin woodsman.
XThe four primitives used in the construction of the tin woodsman
Xare an ARB8, a cylinder, an ellipsoid, and a torus.
XThese four primitives will be duplicated several times,
Xand each copy will be modified using solid editing,
Xto obtain the required shapes.
XThe finished version of this database can be found in
Xthe BRL-CAD Package file ``db/woodsman.g''.
X
X\section{Create Primitives}
X
X\noindent{\tt
X\$ {\em mged woodsman.g} \\
XBRL-CAD Release 3.0 Graphics Editor (MGED) Compilation 82 \\
X    Thu Sep 22 08:08:39 EDT 1988 \\
X    mikel@video.br:/cad/.mged.4d2 \\
X \\
Xwoodsman.g: No such file or directory \\
XCreate new database (y|n)[n]? {\em y} \\
Xattach (nu|tek|tek4109|ps|plot|sgi)[nu]? {\em sgi} \\
XATTACHING sgi (SGI 4d) \\
XUntitled MGED Database (units=mm) \\
Xmged> {\em size 20} \\
Xmged> {\em title A Tin Woodsman} \\
Xmged> {\em in solid8 rpp} \\
XEnter XMIN, XMAX, YMIN, YMAX, ZMIN, ZMAX: {\em -1 1  -1 1  -1 1} \\
Xmged> {\em in torus tor} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vertex: {\em 0 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of normal vector: {\em 0 1 0} \\
XEnter radius 1: {\em 1} \\
XEnter radius 2: {\em 0.2} \\
Xmged> {\em in ellipsoid ellg} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vertex: {\em 0 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vector A: {\em 1 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vector B: {\em 0 0.5 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vector C: {\em 0 0 0.5} \\
Xmged> {\em in cylinder rcc} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vertex: {\em 0 0 0} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of height (H) vector: {\em 2 0 0} \\
XEnter radius: {\em 1} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XAt this point, the screen should look like Figure \ref{wm-prims}.
X
X\section{Copy Primitives and Set Up for Edit}
X
XAlthough eight copies of the ellipsoid and two copies of the cylinder
Xshall be used in the final solid, fewer copies are made initially since there
Xis replication in the editing of these primitives.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em cp ellipsoid e.2} \\
Xmged> {\em cp ellipsoid e.6} \\
Xmged> {\em cp cylinder c.1} \\
Xmged> {\em cp solid8 s.1} \\
Xmged> {\em cp torus t.1} \\
Xmged> {\em Z} \\
Xmged> {\em e e.* c.1 t.1 s.1} \\
Xvectorized in 0 sec \\
Xmged>  \\
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-hat1.ps}
X\caption{Funnel Bowl Cylinder After Rotation.}
X\label{wm-hat1}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-hat2.ps}
X\caption{Funnel Bowl Cylinder After End Scaling.}
X\label{wm-hat2}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-hat3.ps}
X\caption{Funnel Bowl Cylinder After Moving.}
X\label{wm-hat3}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-tube.ps}
X\caption{Funnel Tube Scaled and Positioned.}
X\label{wm-tube}
X\end{figure}
X
X\section{Create Funnel Hat}
X
XThe solid ``cylinder'' has a height vector (``H'') which is 2mm
Xlong.
XThis will be used to good advantage, to make the Tin Woodsman's
Xfunnel hat, with the bowl of the funnel being 2mm high,
Xand the tube of the funnel being 2mm long.
XThe tube of the funnel will point straight up the +Y axis.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em sed c.1} \\
Xmged> {\em Select the ``Rotate'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0 45 90} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThis places the cylinder so that the lines BD and AC are at the outer
Xends of the cylinder.  See Figure \ref{wm-hat1}.
X
XNext, the cylinder is shaped to look like the top of a funnel.
XThe vectors c and d are scaled.
X
X\noindent{\tt
X{\em Select the ``edit menu'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
X{\em Select the ``scale c'' entry in the TGC menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p .1} \\
X{\em Select the ``scale d'' entry in the TGC menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p .1} \\
Xmged> \\
X}
X
XFigure \ref{wm-hat2} is the new shape of the cone.
XNote how the on-screen display records the new lengths of the ``c''
Xand ``d'' vectors.
XThis cone must be moved to the planned locations for the top of the head.
X
X\noindent{\tt
X{\em Select the ``Translate'' entry in the solid edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0 2.2 0} \\
X{\em Select the ``ACCEPT Edit'' entry in the button menu} \\
Xmged> \\
X}
X
XThe bottom of the hat is now properly shaped and positioned.  The
Xnew version of the solid ``c.1'' has been saved in the model database.
XThe editor returns to the viewing state.  See Figure \ref{wm-hat3}.
X
XA copy of the saved ``c.1'' cone is made.  A byproduct of the {\em cp}
Xcommand is to display the new solid, as if the {\em cp c.1 c.2} command
Xhad been immediately followed by an {\em e c.2} command.
XThis new solid will be edited to make the neck of the funnel,
Xwhich is the top of the hat.
XThe ``c.2'' copy of the cone must be
Xscaled down to become a tube and the tube must be placed on top of the
Xcone ``c.1''.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em cp c.1 c.2} \\
Xmged> {\em sed c.2} \\
X{\em Select ``scale A,B'' in the TGC menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0.1} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0 4.2 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XFigure \ref{wm-tube} is the new shape of the funnel tube.
XThe woodsman's hat is comprised of solids c.1 and c.2.
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-head.ps}
X\caption{Head Sphere.}
X\label{wm-head}
X\end{figure}
X
X\section{Building the Head}
X
XThe head of our Tin Woodsman is perfectly spherical, and will be located
Xat coordinates (0, 2, 0).
XWhile it would be possible to duplicate the ellipsoid solid created above,
Xand modifiy it to produce the desired sphere, since all the parameters
Xof the head sphere are known, it is more economical simply to use
Xthe {\em in} command to construct it directly.
XFigure \ref{wm-head} shows the results of this operation.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em in e.1} \\
XEnter solid type: {\em sph} \\
XEnter X, Y, Z of vertex: {\em 0 2 0} \\
XEnter radius: {\em 1} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-collar.ps}
X\caption{The Woodsman's Collar.}
X\label{wm-collar}
X\end{figure}
X
X\section{Building the Collar}
X
XThe torus (primitive t.1) is used to build a collar between the head and
Xthe body.
XThe ring of the collar is scaled to 0.1 of its original size,
Xand repositioned at the base of the head.
XThe results of this step are shown in Figure \ref{wm-collar}.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em sed t.1} \\
X{\em Select ``scale radius 2'' in the TORUS menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0.1} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0 1 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-body.ps}
X\caption{The Woodsman's Body.}
X\label{wm-body}
X\end{figure}
X
X\section{Building the Body}
X
XThe ARB8 (primitive s.1) is used to build the body.
XThe original height of s.1 is only 2mm;  the required
Xlength of the body is 3mm, so the extrusion command is
Xused to adjust the position of the lower (-Y) face of the solid.
XThe result is shown in Figure \ref{wm-body}.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em sed s.1} \\
Xmged> {\em extrude 2367 3} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-arm1.ps}
X\caption{An Upper Arm Prototype.}
X\label{wm-arm1}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-arm2.ps}
X\caption{The Woodsman's Arms.}
X\label{wm-arm2}
X\end{figure}
X
X\section{Building the Arms}
X
XThe ellipsoid primitive (e.2) is used to build the upper and lower parts
Xof the left and right arms.
XThe original solid ``e.2'' is oriented with the major axis of the ellipse
Xoriented along the X axis.
XThe arms need to have the major axis oriented along the Y axis,
Xso first the solid is rotated.
XA more graceful arm is obtained by decreasing the length of
Xthe B and C vectors, and the resulting upper arm solid can be
Xseen in Figure \ref{wm-arm1}.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em sed e.2} \\
X{\em Select ``Rotate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0 45 90} \\
X{\em Select ``edit menu'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
X{\em Select ``scale B'' in the ELLIPSOID menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0.25} \\
X{\em Select ``scale C'' in the ELLIPSOID menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0.25} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThis e.2 solid will now be moved into final position as the upper left arm.
XThen it will be duplicated three times
Xto make the rest of the arm parts.  Finally, each new arm
Xpart will be translated into the proper position,
Xas seen in Figure \ref{wm-arm2}.
X
X\noindent{\tt
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p -1.3 0 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the upper left arm} \\
Xmged> {\em cp e.2 e.3} \\
Xmged> {\em cp e.2 e.4} \\
Xmged> {\em cp e.2 e.5} \\
Xmged> {\em sed e.3} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p -1.3 -2 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the lower left arm} \\
Xmged> {\em sed e.4} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 1.3 0 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the upper right arm} \\
Xmged> {\em sed e.5} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 1.3 -2 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the lower right arm} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-leg1.ps}
X\caption{The First Leg.}
X\label{wm-leg1}
X\end{figure}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-final1.ps}
X\caption{The Tin Woodsman.}
X\label{wm-final1}
X\end{figure}
X
X\section{Building the Legs}
X
XThe ellipsoid primitive (e.6) is used as a prototype
Xto build the upper and lower parts of both legs from.
XThe primitive e.6 is scaled, rotated, and translated
Xinto position as the upper left leg, as seen in Figure \ref{wm-leg1}.
XThen, copies are made and translated to the remaining positions,
Xjust like the arms were.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em sed e.6} \\
X{\em Select ``Rotate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0 45 90} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p -0.5 -3 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the upper left leg} \\
Xmged> {\em cp e.6 e.7} \\
Xmged> {\em cp e.6 e.8} \\
Xmged> {\em cp e.6 e.9} \\
Xmged> {\em sed e.7} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p -0.5 -5 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the lower left leg} \\
Xmged> {\em sed e.8} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0.5 -3 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the upper right leg} \\
Xmged> {\em sed e.9} \\
X{\em Select ``Translate'' in the Solid Edit menu} \\
Xmged> {\em p 0.5 -5 0} \\
X{\em Select ``ACCEPT Edit'' in the Button menu -- This is the lower right leg} \\
X}
X
XFigure \ref{wm-final1} is the view on the screen, the Tin Woodsman.
XTake a moment to use the rotation knobs to view the model from various
Xangles.
X
X\section{Building Regions}
X
XSo far, this example has concentrated on describing the basic shapes
Xinvolved in making the Tin Woodsman, without concern for establishing
Xa proper hierarchical structure.  To illustrate this point,
Xthe various solids will be grouped by purpose and composition.
XFirst, a region will be constructed to contain the torso,
Xand the color of ``cadet blue'' will be assigned:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em r torso.r u s.1} \\
XDefaulting item number to 1001 \\
XCreating region id=1000, air=0, los=100, GIFTmaterial=1 \\
Xmged> {\em mater torso.r} \\
XMaterial = \\
XMaterial?  (CR to skip) {\em plastic} \\
XParam = \\
XParameter string? (CR to skip) {\em [RETURN]} \\
XColor = (No color specified) \\
XColor R G B (0..255)? (CR to skip) {\em 95 159 159} \\
XInherit = 0:  lower nodes (towards leaves) override \\
XInheritance (0|1)? (CR to skip) {\em [RETURN]} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XSecond, a region will be constructed to contain the collar,
Xwhich will be colored red:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em r collar.r u t.1} \\
XDefaulting item number to 1003 \\
XCreating region id=1002, air=0, los=100, GIFTmaterial=1 \\
Xmged> {\em mater collar.r} \\
XMaterial = \\
XMaterial?  (CR to skip) {\em plastic} \\
XParam = \\
XParameter string? (CR to skip)  {\em [RETURN]} \\
XColor = (No color specified) \\
XColor R G B (0..255)? (CR to skip) {\em 255 127 0} \\
XInherit = 0:  lower nodes (towards leaves) override \\
XInheritance (0|1)? (CR to skip)  {\em [RETURN]} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThird, a region will be constructed to contain all the limbs,
Xand a flesh color will be assigned.
XEven though none of the limbs touch each other, note how they
Xare combined with the UNION operation, to create a single
Xobject of uniform composition and color.
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em r limbs.r u e.2 u e.3 u e.4 u e.5 u e.6 u e.7 u e.8 u e.9} \\
XDefaulting item number to 1001 \\
XCreating region id=1000, air=0, los=100, GIFTmaterial=1 \\
Xmged> {\em mater limbs.r} \\
XMaterial = \\
XMaterial?  (CR to skip) {\em plastic} \\
XParam = \\
XParameter string? (CR to skip)  {\em [RETURN]} \\
XColor = 0 0 0 \\
XColor R G B (0..255)? (CR to skip) {\em 255 200 160} \\
XInherit = 0:  lower nodes (towards leaves) override \\
XInheritance (0|1)? (CR to skip)  {\em [RETURN]} \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XNext, the funnel needs to be placed in a region.
XFor the sake of simplicity, the funnel will be solid, rather
Xthan having a hollow center.
XNote that the interior of the funnel overlaps with the top
Xof the Woodsman's head.
XThe funnel can be made ``form fitting'' by subtracting out
Xthe overlap zone:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em r funnel.r u c.1 - e.1 u c.2 - e.1} \\
XDefaulting item number to 1004 \\
XCreating region id=1003, air=0, los=100, GIFTmaterial=1 \\
Xmged> {\em mater funnel.r} \\
XMaterial = \\
XMaterial?  (CR to skip) {\em plastic} \\
XParam = \\
XParameter string? (CR to skip) {\em sh=100} \\
XColor = (No color specified) \\
XColor R G B (0..255)? (CR to skip) {\em 35 107 142} \\
XInherit = 0:  lower nodes (towards leaves) override \\
XInheritance (0|1)? (CR to skip)
Xmged> {\em l funnel.r} \\
Xfunnel.r (len 4) REGION id=1003  (air=0, los=100, GIFTmater=1) -- \\
XMaterial 'plastic' 'sh=100' \\
XColor 35 107 142 \\
X\ \ u c.1 \\
X\ \ - e.1 \\
X\ \ u c.2 \\
X\ \ - e.1 \\
Xmged>
X}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{wm-hat-E.ps}
X\caption{Evaluation of Funnel Hat Region.}
X\label{wm-hat-E}
X\end{figure}
X
XNote how the boolean expression was written.
XThe concept that we need to express here is
Xthe combination of all the funnel parts, minus the
Xportion of the head that overlaps with the inside of the funnel.
XThe natural way to write this is
X\begin{center}
X(c.1 union c.2) - e.1
X\end{center}
Xbut note that there are no grouping operations permitted in the {\em r}
Xcommand.
XFurthermore, for historic reasons, union operations bind more loosely than
Xintersection and subtraction, ie, there are implied groups
Xbetween union operations.  Thus, the expression above needs to be
Xrewritten as the the formula:
X\begin{center}
X(c.1 - e.1) union (c.2 - e.1)
X\end{center}
Xwhich with the binding precedence can be expressed as:
X\begin{center}
Xc.1 - e.1 union c.2 - e.1
X\end{center}
Xwhich is what was entered in the sequence above.
XTo see the effect that this command had on the shape of ``funnel.r'',
Xrun these commands, the effect of which is shown in Figure \ref{wm-hat-E}:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em Z } \\
Xmged> {\em E funnel.r } \\
Xvectorized in 1 sec \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThese regions should be grouped together into a group,
Xfor convenience in referencing.  This can be done with these commands:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em g man.g collar.r funnel.r limbs.r torso.r} \\
Xmged> {\em Z} \\
Xmged> {\em e man.g} \\
Xvectorized in 1 sec \\
Xmged>
X}
X
XThe grouping {\em g} command combined the regions, the Zap command {\em Z}
Xcleared the screen, and the edit {\em e man.g} command drew the whole
Xobject.
XAs an exercise, run
Xthe database structure printing command {\em tree man.g}
Xto obtain a simple depiction of the tree structure that has been created.
XFor the final step of this example, the model will be ray-traced.
XRun the command:
X
X\noindent{\tt
Xmged> {\em rt -s128} \\
Xrt -s50 -M -s128 woodsman.g man.g  \\
Xdb title:  A Tin Woodsman \\
XBuffering single scanlines \\
Xinitial dynamic memory use=35152.\\
XInterpreting command stream in old format\\
XGETTREE: 0.01 CPU secs in 1 elapsed secs (1\%)\\
X                                              \\
X...................Frame     0...................\\
XPREP: 0.01 CPU secs in 0.01 elapsed secs (100\%)\\
Xshooting at 13 solids in 4 regions              \\
Xmodel X(-2,2), Y(-6,7), Z(-2,2)\\
XBeam radius=0.078125 mm, divergance=0 mm/1mm\\
X                                             \\
XSHOT: 3.73 CPU secs in 6 elapsed secs (62.1667\%)\\
XAdditional dynamic memory used=29728. bytes\\
X3515 solid/ray intersections: 1005 hits + 2510 miss\\
Xpruned 28.6\%:  13647 model RPP, 8197 dups, 10740 RPP\\
XFrame     0:    16384 pixels in       3.73 sec =    4392.49 pixels/sec\\
XFrame     0:    16384 rays   in       3.73 sec =    4392.49 rays/sec (RTFM)\\
X\\
XPress RETURN to reattach\\
X{\em [RETURN]} \\
Xmged>
X}
END-of-k.tex
echo x - l.tex
sed 's/^X//' >l.tex << 'END-of-l.tex'
X\chapter{BUILDING A ROBOT ARM}
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{robot.ps}
X\caption{The RMIT Robot Arm.}
X\label{robot}
X\end{figure}
X
XThe model shown in Figure \ref{robot}
Xwill be described in a step by step instructions
Xon how to build and display this model.
X
XThis is the MGED input file:
X
X\begin{verbatim}
Xin btm	box	0 0 0    0 -90 0      40 0 0   0 0 6
Xin btm1	box	0 -90 0  0 -61.549 0  40 0 0   0 0 6
Xin rad	rcc	20 -150 0   0 0 6   8
Xin cyl	rcc	20 -45 6    0 0 30  20
Xin cyl1 rcc	20 -45 0 0 0 36 15.5
Xin cyl2 rcc	20 -45 0 0 0 36 12.5
Xin hole rcc	8 -8 0   0 0 6   3
Xin hole1 rcc	32 -8 0  0 0 6   3
Xcp hole1 hole2
