X\chapter{RT MATERIAL TYPE, PROPERTIES, and COLOR}
X
XFirst the solids must be formed into a "region", eg:
X
X{\em\center
Xr ball u torus u tube-hole
X}
X
XTo change material type, properties and color use the "mater" command:
X
X{\tt
Xmged> {\em mater base} \\
XMaterial = \\
XMaterial?  (CR to skip) {\em plastic} \\
XParam = \\
XParameter string? (CR to skip) {\em sh=10 dl=0.2 sp=0.8 re=0.75} \\
XColor = (No color specified) \\
XColor R G B (0..255)? (CR to skip) {\em 112 219 147} \\
XInherit = 0:  lower nodes (towards leaves) override \\
XInheritance (0|1)? (CR to skip) {\em 0} \\
Xmged> \\
X}
X
XFor the values in Parameter String for material ``Plastic'',
Xyou can enter such things as:
X"shinyness (sh)",
X"specular lighting fraction (sp)",
X"diffuse lighting fraction (di)",
X"transmission fraction (tr)",
X"reflection fraction (re)", and
X"refractive index (ri)".
XTwo formulas must hold to keep the material ``physical'':
Xsp + di=1.0, and tr + re=1.0.
X
XSuggested values for these properties are listed below:
X
X{\center sh=10, dl=0.2, sp=0.8, re=0.75}
X
XNOTE:  Not all of these fields need to be input, you
Xcan use the system defaults for the rest.
X
XTo display objects in different colors on the screen, each object must
Xbe a region with its own material properties and colors.  All regions must be
Xdisplayed on screen before a ray tracing can be performed (region objects can
