X\chapter{RAYTRACING YOUR CREATION}
X
XOnce you have finished creating all your solids, positioned them in
Xtheir correct relationships to each other, formed all your regions (forming
Xyour finished object), created groups (if required), you can now do a ray-
Xtracing of the view displayed on the screen.
X
XNote!  If you want to display solids or objects (collection of solids
Xregioned together) of different colors, each of the solids or objects must be
Xseparate regions so you can give them a specific color.
X
XThe raytracing command is
X{\em\center
X  rt [-s\#]
X}
X
XThis command produces a color shaded image of the solids or objects on
Xthe display.  This color shaded image  will appear on a frame buffer display.
XThe resolution of the image (number of rays) is equal to "\#" from the "-s"
Xoption.  If the "-s" option is absent, 50x50 ray solution will be used (very
Xcourse raytrace).  The higher the "-s" option the better the raytracing, but
Xit takes longer to display.
XRecommended optimun value of "-s" option for picture
Xquality and speed of display is 256!.  Some examples follow:
X
X{\em
X             rt -s128 \\
X             rt \\
X             rt -s256 \\
X}
X
XWhen the rt command is given the text and graphic window will appear,
Xthen the frame buffer starts to appear (the picture window).  The first scaned
Xdisplay will be what was previously stored in it, it will then over write it
Xwith your picture; sometimes two buffer scans are displayed before yours.
X
XThe default background color is blue with steel grey colored solids and
Xobjects.  The terminal will beep when the scanned picture is finished; press
Xreturn to get back to the "text and graphic" window.
X
XWith the blue background it is sometimes hard to visualize the raytraced
Xpicture; two things you can do to improve the situation is:
X     (a)  Make separate regions for all solids and objects, so that you can
Xassign a specific color to each region; this can be a time consuming task if
Xyou have a lot of solids and objects.
X     (b)  Construct as a separate region, three thin flat plates to form two
Xwalls with a bottom, as shown below; using "make name arb8",
Xthen solid editing this arb8, using move faces to the required thickness,
Xthen use command "cp"
X(copy command) to make two more copies which you can rotate to their
Xrespective relationships, then translate all three into the correct positions
Xrelative to each other and the solids and objects you are displaying.
X
XThe advantage of doing this is to give the light source something
Xto reflect off, giving back lighting; improving contrast considerably.
XWith the
Xthree plates formed into their own region you can delete them from the screen
Xwith the "d" command, rotate your creation then re-display your plates (walls)
Xwith the "e" command to do another rt, the walls need to be deleted from the
Xdisplay when you rotate your objects,
Xotherwise everything will rotate together.
X
X                                   Figure
X
XA bonus of having constructed these three walls is that you can quickly
Xchange the material type to "mirror" so that you can get reflections of the
Xthree hidden faces.
X
X\chapter{CONCLUSIONS}
X
XMGED performs two basic functions:
Xviewing and editing.
XThe standard viewing capabilities of zooming, slewing,
Xslicing, and rotation are available.
XLikewise, all the standard editing features are also available.
XThe user easily traverses the hierarchical data structure, applying
Xthe editing functions of rotation, translation, and scaling to any
Xposition in the hierarchy.
XThe hierarchical structure can be modified and regrouped and regions
Xcreated and modified.
XSpecific parameter editing can also be applied to the solids to produce
Xany shape solid desired.
X
XFor several decades, the production and modification of geometric models
Xsuitable for sophisticated engineering analysis
Xhas been a slow, labor-intensive procedure.
XIn an effort to improve the response time of geometric models,
Xthe Ballistic
XResearch Laboratory (BRL) has developed an interactive model editor
Xfor their combinatorial solid geometry modeling system (The BRL-CAD Package).
XThe user interface to the geometry of these models
Xis a program called the Multi-device Graphics Editor (MGED)
Xthat is designed to replace the
Xtraditional manual method
Xfor producing and modifying model databases.
XUsing MGED, the geometric models
Xare interactively viewed, modified, and constructed with immediate visual
Xfeedback at each step.
XWhen desired, the MGED editor can be operated without the need for
Xexplicit numerical input
Xand opens a new dimension in the model building process.
XMGED has made great gains in reducing the bottleneck in
Xthe creation of high resolution geometric models.
END-of-m.tex
