X\chapter{TUTORIALS}
XEleven tutorials with illustrations are provided to give the user a
Xstep-by-step walk-through of the basic capabilities of the graphics
Xeditor. Standard login and logout procedures should be followed prior to
Xbeginning and after ending the tutorials.
X
XTutorial one describes accessing of each of the MGED states.
XTutorials two through six describe the use of
X{\bf SOL EDIT}
X(solid edit) to alter the shapes of several primitives (solids).
XTutorials seven and eight describe the use of
X{\bf OBJ EDIT}
X(object edit) to alter the shape of objects (which are made of other objects
Xand ultimately solids).
XTutorial nine describes the use of
X{\bf OBJ PATH}
X(object matrix selection) control the extent of the effects of an object edit.
XTutorial ten describes the use of the viewing functions.
XTutorial eleven describes the construction of an object from solids and
Xother objects.
X
XEach of the tutorials will use the solids contained the MGED database called
X``prim.g''.
XThese can be obtained by making a copy of ``db/prim.g''
Xfrom the BRL-CAD Package distribution tree.  It is important to make
Xa copy of the database and work with that, rather than using the
Xsupplied one.  Changes made during the editing process are written
Xto the database when they are {\sl accepted}.
X
XThe first tutorial shows a sample invocation dialogue.  All other
Xtutorials start at the first MGED prompt ({\tt mged> }). If the user
Xwishes to continue from one tutorial to the next without leaving MGED, issue
Xthe {\bf press reset} command before starting each tutorial.
XUser input will be shown in an
X{\em emphasized} font, and MGED output will appear in a {\tt typewriter}
Xfont.  If the user input is shown on the same line as a prompt, the
Xinput is literal.  If the user input is shown on a line by itself,
Xit is a directive, and is entered in an appropriate fashion.
X
X\section{States Within the Edit Process}
X
XIn this tutorial, the user will invoke MGED on a file called ``prim.g'';
Xattach a {\sl display manager\/}; explore the various MGED states;
Xand finally, exit MGED.  A MGED database has a treelike structure.  The
Xleaves are the individual solids, and the other nodes are groupings
Xof those solids.  The solid editing functions are concerned with defining
Xand modifying the leaves, and the object editing functions operate
Xon groups, which are Boolean combinations of solids.  One useful mental
Xmodel is to envision solid editing as operating directly on a leaf and
Xobject editing as operating on the arc connecting a pair of nodes.  The
Xobject edit will affect everything below the selected arc (this is why
Xthere is an additional state transition when object editing).
X
X\subsection{Viewing State}
X
XThe first task is to invoke MGED.  This tutorial will assume the user
Xhas a copy of the ``prim.g'' database in the current directory.
X
X\noindent
X{\tt \$ }{\em mged prim.g}\\
X{\tt BRL-CAD Release 3.0 Graphics Editor (MGED) Compilation 82}\\
X{\tt Thu Sep 22 08:08:39 EDT 1988}\\
X{\tt mike@video.brl.mil:/cad/.mged.4d2}\\
X
X\noindent
X{\tt attach (nu|tek|tek4109|ps|plot|sgi)[nu]? }{\em sgi}\\
X{\tt ATTACHING sgi (SGI 4d)}\\
X{\tt Primitive Objects (units=mm)}\\
X{\tt mged> }\\
X
XThe first three lines give information about which version of MGED is running,
Xwhen it was compiled, and who compiled it.  The next line is the display
Xmanager attach prompt.  This prompt provides a list of available display
Xmanagers, then shows what the default will be (selected if the user answers
Xwith a carriage return).  In this case, the Silicon Graphics 4d display
Xmanager was selected, as is noted by the following line.
XNext the title of the database and
Xthe unit of measurement used in the database are printed,
Xand finally, the first prompt is issued.
XAt this point MGED has loaded ``prim.g''; attached the SGI display;
Xand is awaiting commands.  Attaching a display also causes what
Xis known as the MGED {\sl faceplate} to be drawn on the graphics display.
X
XThe faceplate has several features of interest.  In the upper left corner
Xof the display, is a box which always shows the current MGED {\sl state}.
XThis can be one of six states:  {\bf VIEWING}, {\bf SOL PICK},
X{\bf SOL EDIT}, {\bf OBJ PICK}, {\bf OBJ PATH}, or {\bf OBJ EDIT}.
X
XImmediately below, is the menu area.  The only menu item initially shown is
Xone labeled {\bf BUTTON MENU}.  This menu item toggles the display of the
Xbutton menu entries when {\sl selected} (more on selection later).
X
XAt the bottom of the display are two status lines.  The first line
Xcontains information about the current view.
XThe entry labeled {\bf cent=} gives the {\sl model space} coordinates
Xof the dot in the center of the display.
XThe entry labeled {\bf sz=} reflects the current size in model units of
Xthe {\sl viewing cube}.  The viewing cube is a mathematical construct
Xcentered on the the dot in the center of the display.  The {\bf ang=}
Xdisplay shows the current rate of rotation in each of the three axes.
XThe bottom line is used for several kinds of information.
XIn the {\bf VIEWING} state, it displays the title of the database.
X
X\noindent
X{\tt mged>\ }{\em e arb8}\\
X{\tt vectorized in 0 sec}\\
X{\tt mged>\ }{\em size 12}\\
X{\tt mged> }\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-top-vw.ps}
X\caption{``arb8'' Top View.}
X\label{t1-top-vw}
X\end{figure}
X
XThe {\bf e} command causes the named object(s) -- a solid named ``arb8''
Xin this case
X-- to be displayed, and the {\bf size} command sets the size of the
Xviewing cube. Figure \ref{t1-top-vw} shows what the display currently
Xlooks like.  In this view, the X-axis is to the right, the Y-axis points
Xup, and the Z-axis is perpendicular to (poking out of) the screen.
X
X\noindent
X{\em Twist the {\bf Y ROT} knob clockwise and back.}\\
X{\em Twist the {\bf X ROT} knob counterclockwise and back.}\\
X
XThese knobs, along with the {\bf Z ROT} knob, rotate the viewing cube.
XUse of the rotation
Xknobs allows the user to view the model from any orientation.
XTurning a knob clockwise causes a rotation in the positive direction,
Xwhile turning a knob counterclockwise causes a negative rotation
X(right-hand rule).  The knobs are rate based, not position based;
Xonce a rotation has been started, it will continue until the
Xknob is returned to zero (or the {\bf zeroknobs} button is pressed).
XRotations are about the viewing cube (screen) axes, not the model axes.
XSystems without knobs can use the {\bf knob} command.
X
X\noindent
X{\em Move the mouse (or pen) until the cursor is in the {\bf BUTTON MENU}
Xblock and then press the middle mouse button (depress the pen).}\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-rot-vw.ps}
X\caption{``arb8'' Rotated View.}
X\label{t1-rot-vw}
X\end{figure}
X
XPressing the middle mouse button (or the pen) {\sl selects} something.
XWhen the cursor is inside the menu area, a selection
Xcauses the event described by the menu item to occur.
XSelecting {\bf BUTTON MENU} causes the button menu to appear on the left
Xside of the screen. The {\bf BUTTON MENU} menu item is
Xa toggle; subsequent selection of this item will cause the button menu
Xto disappear.
XFigure \ref{t1-rot-vw} shows the new display.
X
X\noindent
X{\em Move the cursor from the menu area to a point near the
Xupper left corner of the solid and select it (press the center mouse
Xbutton).}\\
X
XIn the {\bf VIEWING} state, making a selection while outside of the menu
Xarea will move the selected point to the center of the display.  Look
Xcarefully at the center of the display; the point just selected is now
Xlocated at the center dot. Use the {\bf center} command to reset any
Xtranslations made with the mouse.
X
X\noindent
X{\tt mged> }{\em center 0 0 0}\\
X{\tt mged> }\\
X
XFrom the {\bf VIEWING} state, the user will normally transition to either the
X{\bf SOL PICK} or {\bf OBJ PICK} state.
XThe {\bf SOL PICK} state is selected by:
X\begin{itemize}
X\item Selecting the {\bf Solid Illum} button menu entry, or,
X\item Pressing the {\bf sill} button (this button may be labeled
Xusing some variation of ``Solid Illum''), or,
X\item Typing {\bf press sill}.
X\end{itemize}
XSimilar entries ({\bf Object Illum}) and ({\bf oill}) exist for transitioning
Xinto the {\bf OBJ PICK} state.
XIn general, the {\bf press} command is the basic mechanism (type
X{\bf press help} for a list of available commands).  Most of the press
Xcommands have been mapped onto a button box if it is available,
X and some of the
Xmost common are also mapped into the {\bf BUTTON MENU} so they can
Xaccessed without letting go of the mouse.
X
X\subsection{Solid Pick State}
X
X\noindent
X{\em Place MGED in the {\bf SOL PICK} state using one of the
Xabove mechanisms.}\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-sol-pk.ps}
X\caption{MGED In Solid Pick State.}
X\label{t1-sol-pk}
X\end{figure}
X
XUpon entering the {\bf SOL PICK} state, the display will look similar to
XFigure \ref{t1-sol-pk}.  The {\bf SOL PICK} state used to select which
Xof the displayed solids is to be edited.  Note that the color of the
Xsolid has changed from red to white.  The screen is divided into as many
Xhorizontal zones as there are solids displayed, and each zone is
Xassigned to one solid.  As the mouse is moved vertically through each
Xzone, the corresponding solid is highlighted (``illuminated'') by
Xdrawing it in white.   In this instance, there is only one solid being
Xdisplayed, so this state is relatively uninteresting.
XIf the system being used has no mouse, there is no reason to enter the
X{\bf SOL PICK} state.  The user will instead transition directly to
Xthe {\bf SOL EDIT} state using the {\bf sed} command.
X
X\noindent
X{\tt mged> }{\em press reject}\\
X{\tt mged> }{\em e ellg}\\
X{\tt mged> }\\
X{\em Press the {\bf sill} button}\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-2s-pk.ps}
X\caption{MGED In Solid Pick with Two Solids.}
X\label{t1-2s-pk}
X\end{figure}
X
XNote that the first action taken was to {\sl reject} the edit.  Any time MGED
Xis not in the {\bf VIEWING} state, a {\sl reject} command (via
X{\bf press}, button, or mouse) discards all editing changes accumulated
Xsince the last transition out of the {\bf VIEWING} state, and places
XMGED in the {\bf VIEWING} state.
XThe display should now look similar to Figure \ref{t1-2s-pk}.
XNotice that one solid is white and
Xthe name of that solid is displayed in the upper left corner of the
Xdisplay, as well as in the bottom status line. The solid to be edited is
Xselected by moving the mouse up and down until the zone corresponding to
Xthe desired solid is reached. Once the appropriate zone is reached, select it.
XThis selects a solid, and once a solid is selected,
XMGED enters the {\bf SOL EDIT} state.
X
X\subsection{Solid Edit State}
X
X\noindent
X{\tt mged> }{\em d ellg}\\
X{\tt mged> }\\
X{\em Select the solid called ``arb8''.}\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-sol-ed.ps}
X\caption{Solid Edit State.}
X\label{t1-sol-ed}
X\end{figure}
X
XThe {\bf d} commmand removes something from the display.  In this
Xcase, the solid ``ellg'' was removed to reduce clutter.
XThe display should now look like Figure \ref{t1-sol-ed}.
XWhen MGED enters the solid edit state, the following occurs:
X\begin{itemize}
X\item The solid selected for editing remains illuminated,
X\item The solid is labeled,
X\item The coordinates (or dimensions) associated with the labels,
Xand other information is displayed to the right of the menu area,.
X\item If the solid is a member of one or more groups, a similar set
Xof coordinates called the {\sl PATH} is displayed immediately below
Xthe the first set of coordinates,
X\item The {\bf *SOLID EDIT*} menu is displayed, and,
X\item A solid specific edit menu (in this case the {\bf ARB MENU})
Xis displayed.
X\end{itemize}
X
XThe {\bf *SOLID EDIT*} menu provides access to generic operations (translation, rotation
Xand scaling) common to all solids.
XThe solid specific edit menu is a list of solid type specific editing operations.
XSelecting one of the solid specific edit menus causes a submenu with solid type specific
Xchoices to be displayed.  To remove this submenu, select either the
X{\bf RETURN} item in the submenu, or the {\bf edit menu} item in the
X{\bf *SOLID EDIT*} menu.
X
XIt is in this state that the solid is altered to meet the modeler's
Xrequirements. The shape, positioning, and orientation of the solid is
Xchanged using numeric keyboard input, positioning of the mouse, or by
Xuse of the knobs.  Once the solid has been altered, the edit is
Xeither accepted or rejected.  Accepting the edit causes all changes
Xmade to be written to the database; rejecting the edit ``throws them
Xaway''. Either operation will terminate the edit session and return MGED
Xto the {\bf VIEWING} state.
X
X\noindent
X{\em Reject the edit.}\\
X
X\subsection{Object Pick State}
X
X\noindent
X{\em Place MGED in the {\bf OBJ PICK} state.}\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-obj-pk.ps}
X\caption{Object Pick State.}
X\label{t1-obj-pk}
X\end{figure}
X
XFigure \ref{t1-obj-pk} shows what the display looks like when in the
X{\bf OBJ PICK} state. As with the {\bf SOL PICK} state, a single solid is
Xselected.  This solid becomes the reference solid for the object edit.
XIn the {\bf OBJ PICK} state, the solid will be shown
Xas a member of one or more objects.  Less obvious is the fact that the
Xlocal axes associated with the selected solid are the axes used for the
Xentire object during the object edit.
X
X\subsection{Object Path State}
X
X\noindent
X{\em Select ``arb8''.}\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-obj-ph.ps}
X\caption{Object Path Selection State.}
X\label{t1-obj-ph}
X\end{figure}
X
XMGED transitions into the {\bf OBJ PATH} state once a solid has been
Xpicked from {\bf OBJ PICK}. Figure \ref{t1-obj-ph} is the display in
Xthe {\bf OBJ PATH} state.  When in this state the extent of the editing
Xoperation is set.  Everything below the editing point is affected by the
Xedit.  The editing point is shown by the {\sl MATRIX} label in the
Xdisplay.  It is shown as {\bf [MATRIX]} in the upper left part of the
Xdisplay and as {\bf \_\_MATRIX\_\_} in the second status line.  The editing
Xpoint is chosen with the same mechanism used by {\bf SOL PICK} and
X{\bf OBJ PICK}.  This time, there is one horizontal zone for each node in
Xthe path between the root and selected leaf.  Moving the mouse up and down
Xmoves the editing point up and down in the tree.  Once again, having a
Xsimple database and only one object in view makes for a relatively
Xuninteresting situation.
X
X\subsection{Object Edit State}
X
X\noindent
X{\em Select the editing point above ``arb8''.}\\
X
X\begin{figure}
X\centering \includegraphics{t1-obj-ed.ps}
X\caption{Object Edit State.}
X\label{t1-obj-ed}
X\end{figure}
X
XMGED is now in the {\bf OBJ EDIT} state and the display should look like
XFigure \ref{t1-obj-ed}.
XWhen MGED enters the object edit state, the following occurs:
X\begin{itemize}
X\item The reference solid remains illuminated,
X\item The reference solid is labeled,
X\item The information associated with the labels is displayed to the right
Xof the menu area, and
X\item The {\bf *OBJ EDIT*} menu is displayed.
X\end{itemize}
X
XThe {\bf OBJ EDIT} state is used to modify the
XHomogeneous Transform Matrix selected during the {\bf OBJ PATH} state.
XPermissible operations include uniform and affine scaling of the objects,
Xas well as translation and rotation.
XAs with the {\bf SOL EDIT} state, MGED accepts changes entered using
Xthe keyboard, mouse or knobs.
X
XThis concludes the first tutorial.  Examples of the appearance of MGED
Xin each of the six states have been given, along with some idea of what
Xeach of the states is used for.  All that remains is to reject the current
Xedit, and exit MGED.  Strictly speaking the {\bf q} command could be entered
Xdirectly, but doing so, can become a dangerous habit.
X
X\noindent
X{\em Select {\bf REJECT Edit} using the mouse.}\\
X{\em Press the {\bf reject} button.}\\
X{\tt mged> }{\em d arb8}\\
X{\tt mged> }{\em q}\\
X{\tt \$ }\\
END-of-t1.tex
